		Me.txtHelpCurrents.Text = "CURRENTS" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  Determine the set and drift (velocity) of the tidal current at a desired time, using data extracted from a Tidal Current Table, as taught in " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the USPS Advanced Piloting (AP) 85/86 course or the AP 2011 (or AP 2004) course (see Operation).  (This is not a tidal current prediction program.)  The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Current tool uses a form similar to the worksheet of the AP 85/86 course." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:  For determining the tidal current at a reference station, required inputs are the desired time and the times of the slack and maximum " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(flood or ebb) that bracket the desired time, and the velocity and set of the maximum, obtained from Table 1 of the tidal current table.  For determining " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the tidal current at a substation, additional required inputs are the Table 2 differences for times and velocities of the slack(s) and maximum(s).  When " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "determining the tidal current at a substation, it is often not obvious which slack and maximum bracket the desired time, because of the Table 2 time " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "differences.  In those cases, the other slack and maximum Table 1 and Table 2 data can be entered to help determine the proper slack and maximum to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "use.  Required times cannot be left blank, even if the required time is 0000.  All other inputs are optional, and can be used when a printed record of a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "complete tide determination is desired." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note:  Tidal current tables use standard time.  The user must convert daylight savings times to standard times before extracting data from the Tidal " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Current Table." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When entering the Table 2 time differences, use the format of the Tidal Current Table, i.e. the sign goes with the hour, even if the hour is zero.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "However, plus signs and leading zeros can be omitted." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The program will recognize when the selected times of slack and maximum  cross midnight." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Activating the ""Calculate"" button starts the calculation.  Once the localized times and velocities are calculated, the user must determine which slack and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "which maximum are the ones that bracket the desired time, and check the appropriate check boxes.  (For technical reasons, this selection is not done " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "automatically.)  Only one slack and one maximum can be selected.  As soon as a second check box is checked, the calculation is completed using the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "selected option.  If only one slack time and only one maximum time are entered, their boxes will be automatically checked and the calculation completed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For ""normal"" locations, i.e. those where there is little or no hydraulic current, there are options to determine the velocity factor by doing the calculation " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "mathematically (the default), where the actual values are used; or by using Table 3A values (as taught in AP 85/86), where the actual entering " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "arguments are rounded to tabular values; or to do the calculation using the ""50-90 Rule"" (as taught in AP 2011 and AP 2004).  For locations where there " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is a strong hydraulic current, the Table 3B option should be used." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When switching from one option to another there is no need to activate the ""Calculate"" button." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Choices that would be circled on a paper worksheet will appear in bold type." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Activating the ""Clear"" button clears all inputs and outputs." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  As with tidal current tables, the computation assumes that the increase (flood) and decrease (ebb) of the tidal current velocity " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "conform to simple sine curves.  This is often not true, so the tidal current velocities obtained will be approximate. The most accurate results are obtained " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "using mathematical calculation for the velocity factor.  Using the Table 3A option adds a bit of error to the theoretical (sine) calculation, and the ""50-90 " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Rule"" can, but will not necessarily, impose a  larger error, but these errors are usually no more than a half a knot, and are probably less relevant than if " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the flood and ebb do not conform to a sine curve.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Localized velocities are rounded to hundredths of a knot, except for the ""50-90 Rule"" where they are rounded to tenths of a knot.  The predicted " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "velocity is rounded to tenths of a knot." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Celestial Tools uses the method of the PREDICTION OF CURRENT AND DIRECTION form of AP 2011 and AP 2004 for the ""50-90 Rule"".  Note that if the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Time Difference converted to minutes (line (4) of the form) is not evenly divisible by three, then Time#3 on line (6) will differ from the later of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "bracketed times (line (1)) by one minute." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
