		Me.txtHelpTides.Text = "TIDES" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  Determine the height of the tide at a desired time, using data extracted from a Tide Table, as taught in the USPS Advanced Piloting (AP) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "85/86 course or the AP 2004 (or later) course (see Operation).  (This is not a tide prediction program.)  The Tide tool uses a form similar to the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "worksheet of the AP 85/86 course." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Determine vertical clearance and depth under keel." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:  For determining the tide at a reference station, required inputs are the desired time and the times and heights of the high and low tides " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "that bracket the desired time, obtained from Table 1 of the Tide Table.  For determining the tide at a substation, additional required inputs are the Table " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "2 differences for times and heights of the high and low tides.  Times cannot be left blank, even if the required time is 0000.  Heights are shown in feet, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "but can be entered in feet, meters, centimeters, or any other linear unit, but the same unit must be used throughout, and the resultant heights will be in " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "that unit.  (It is recommended that centimeters be converted to meters.)  All other inputs are optional, and can be used when a printed record of a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "complete tide determination is desired." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note:  Tide tables use standard time.  The user must convert daylight savings times to standard times before extracting data from the Tide Table." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When entering the Table 2 time differences, use the format of the tide table, i.e. the sign goes with the hour, even if the hour is zero.  However, plus " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "signs and leading zeros can be omitted.  Table 2 height differences need not be preceded by a plus sign (+) if additive, but must be preceded by a minus " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sign (-) if subtractive or an asterisk (*) if Table 2 expressed it as a ratio (indicated by an asterisk).  Omitted zeros for height and time difference inputs " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "are added automatically for the sake of a printed record." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The program will recognize when the times that bracket the desired time cross midnight." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Activating the ""Calculate"" button completes the calculation, using the selected option." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "There are options to determine the height of tide correction by doing the calculation mathematically (the default), where the actual values are used; or " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "by using Table 3 values (as taught in AP 85/86), where the actual entering arguments are rounded to tabular values; or to do the calculation using a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "simplified ""Rule of Twelfths"" (as taught in AP 2004, a form of what is more commonly known as the ""Rule of Tenths"", and is not the usual presentation of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the Rule of Twelfths), where times are rounded to whole hours and percentages are used for each time increment; or to do the calculation using an " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "alternate form of  the ""Rule of Twelfths"".  When using the simplified ""Rules of Twelfths"", if the half cycle duration is significantly different from six hours, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the results may not be satisfactory.  If this is true, the alternate version of the ""Rules of Twelfths"", giving more accurate results, should be used.  A rule " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of thumb is if the difference is 60 minutes or more the alternate form should be used, but the alternate form can always be used, giving more accurate " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "results, regardless of the difference. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When switching from one option to another there is no need to activate the ""Calculate"" button." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Choices that would be circled on a paper worksheet will appear in bold type." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Activating the ""Clear"" button clears all inputs and outputs." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Activating the ""Calculate Vertical Clearances"" button, which can be done with or without a previous depth calculation, opens another window which is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "used to calculate the vertical clearance (defined in the AP course as the clearance between the water and an overhead bridge) and the actual clearance " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(between the highest point on the boat and the bridge), and the depth clearance (between the boat's keel and the bottom).  Inputs are expected in " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "feet or meters, with the same unit must be used throughout, and the results will be in that unit.  Height of tide at desired time is required for either " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculation. All previously entered or calculated values are cleared, except if a height if tide calculation was already made, it will automatically be used " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "for this function, but can be changed if desired. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & " " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For Vertical Clearance, additional required inputs are the height of the object to be cleared (from the chart), the mean tidal range (from Table 2), the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "mean tide level (from Table 2), and, if actual clearance is desired, the height of the highest point on the boat.  For Depth Under Keel, additional required " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "inputs are the depth (from the chart) and the boat's draft.  (Charted heights and depths are given in whole units and must be entered as such.)  Either " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculation can be done by itself, or both cacluations can be done simultaneously.  When Vertical Clearance is calculated, the intermediate step of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "height of MHW above MLLW is also shown. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Activating the ""Clear"" button clears all inputs and outputs." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  As with tide tables, the computation assumes that the rise and fall of the tides conform to simple cosine curves.  This is often " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "not true, so the heights obtained will be approximate. The most accurate results are obtained using mathematical calculation for the height of tide " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "correction.  Using the Table 3 option adds a bit of error to the theoretical (cosine) calculation; the alternate form of the ""Rule of Twelfths"" generally " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "imposes a  larger error, but these errors are usually no more than a half a unit (more significant if the unit is meters, less significant if the unit is feet), " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and are probably less relevant than if the rise and fall do not conform to a cosine curve.  The simplified form of  the ""Rule of Twelfths"", however, can " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "impose a significant and dangerous error if the half cycle duration is significantly different from six hours" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "All height results are rounded to the nearest tenth of a unit." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
