		Me.txtHelpTwoBearings.Text = "DISTANCE BY TWO BEARINGS/FIX BY CROSS BEARINGS/COURSE MADE GOOD BY THREE BEARINGS" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  Calculate the distance to a fixed object by taking two bearings on the object from a moving vessel.  This works in the same manner as " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """doubling the angle on the bow"", but works for any allowed combination of bearings.  It will also calculate the distance from the position of the second " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "bearing to the point where the object is abeam (closest point of approach), and, if the required data is provided, the time required to get to this point " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and the time of arrival at this point.  (This tool does the calculations of Bowditch 2002 Table 18 - Distance of an Object by Two Bearings.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "It assumes that the vessel maintains its course and speed, and that the vessel is approaching the object, not moving away from it." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Calculate a fix from two cross bearings on charted objects with no (or little) vessel movement between the bearings, or a running fix if there is vessel " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "movement between the bearings.  (Note:  To calculate a fix by range and bearing, see Help>The Sailings>Other applications.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Calculate the course made good (CMG) using three bearings on the same object at different times and the time or distance intervals between them, as " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "might be done if it is suspected that an unknown current has thrown the vessel off track." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Distance by two bearings:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Select whether the bearings will be Relative (bow bearings, the default), True, Magnetic, or Compass.  If True, Magnetic, or Compass is selected, enter " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the vessel's course (whole degrees, from 0 to 359), as the type selected.  If Relative is selected, enter the first and second bow (relative) bearings to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the object, limited to whole degrees from 1 to 90.  (0° would be a collision course; over 90° the vessel would already be moving away from the object.)  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "These can be clockwise or counterclockwiese, i.e. with respect to the starboard or port bow, with no sign.  If True, Magnetic, or Compass is selected, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "enter the first and second bearings as the type selected (whole degrees, 0 to 359)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Enter either the distance traveled between the two bearings (as actual distance or as start and end knotmeter log values, Log1 and Log2, limited to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "9999.9nm) or the speed and running time (as actual running time or start and end times, Time1 and Time2, in hhmm format).  Log1 and Time1 are " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "associated with the first bearing; Log2 and Time2 are associated with the second bearing.  Distance can be entered with tenth of a nautical mile " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "resolution up to 99.9 nautical miles (a much larger than practical value). Speed can be entered with tenth of a knot resolution up to 99.9 knots.  (The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "speed value is either a constant speed or average speed based on the actual conditions.)  Run Time can be entered in integer hours and integer " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "minutes, or just integer minutes.  If an hour value is entered, minutes are limited to 59.  If no (or zero) hour value is entered, minutes are limited to 99 " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(1.65 hours).  If a minute value greater than 59 is entered, the hour box is disabled.  If the entered speed and time result in a distance greater than " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "99.9 nautical miles, an error message will be generated.  If Log1 is greater than Log2 an error message will be generated.  If Time1 is later than Time2 " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "an error message will be generated.  (The program does not consider this to be a run that crosses midnight.  If this is actually the case, it is best to use " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Run Time.)  Press the ""Calculate Distance"" button to get the distance from the position of the second bearing to the object, the distance off that the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "object will be when abeam, and the distance that would have to be traveled before the object is abeam.  If speed and run time were entered, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculated distance from the position of the second bearing to the point where the object is abeam will also be displayed.  If the times of the bearings " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rather than the run time are entered, the time that the object will be abeam will also be displayed.  If Time1 and Time2 were entered, calculated run time " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "will also be displayed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Pressing the ""Clear"" button clears the input and output data." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Switching from one bearing type to another clears the input and output data unless an illegal input value remains, which must be corrected first." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Fix by cross bearings:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Enter the latitudes and longitudes of the two observed objects, obtained from a chart.  Enter the true bearings from the vessel to the two objects, or " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "check the ""Reciprocal bearings"" box and enter the true reciprocal bearings from the two objects to the vessel.  Although bearings will generally be in " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "whole degrees, values up to 359.9° can be entered, with a maximum of five characters including a decimal point.  Press the ""Calculate Fix from Cross " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Bearings"" button and the latitude and longitude of the fix will be displayed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "To establish a running fix,  use The Sailings, Destination L and Lo to advance the position of the earlier charted object to the later time, and use this " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "position for L1 and Lo1.  (The earlier and later charted objects could be the same.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Bearings are best done with a hand bearing compass, but sighting over the vessel's compass can be done.  Magnetic or compass bearings must be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "converted to true bearings.  Ideally the smaller angle formed by the cross bearings is 90°, giving the least fix error due to bearing error, but keeping the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "smaller angle from 45° to 135° is recommended.  (Some sources, e.g. AP 85/86, recommend 40° to 140°; other sources, e.g. AP 2004, recommend 30° " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to 150°.)  If the entered bearings are outside the 45° to 135° range a message will be displayed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Pressing the ""Clear"" button clears the input and output data, and unchecks the ""Use reciprocal bearings"" checkbox if checked." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Course made good by three bearings and intervals between them:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Enter the three bearings taken on the same object and the intervals between the first and second bearing and the second and third bearing.  Bearings " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "must be in whole degrees, and can be true, magnetic, or compass, with the resulting CMG in the same units.  Intervals can be time between bearings or " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the distance traveled between bearings.    Time or distance can be used if speed is constant; distance must be used if speed has changed.  Intervals do " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "not have to be the actual values as long as the ratios are correct.  For instance, if the times or distances between bearings are the same, the CMG will " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "be correct as long as the same number is used in both Interval boxes.  (Up to five characters, including a decimal point, are accepted.)  If, for instance, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the first interval is 1nm and the second is 2nm, one and two, two and four, etc., can be entered in the two Interval boxes.  (In practice, the intervals " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "are usually made the same to make the determination by chartwork easier.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Bearings must be monotonically increasing or decreasing.  If they do not appear as such, as would happen if zero degrees was crossed (e.g. 345°, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "355°, 5°), a message will appear asking for confirmation." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Pressing the ""Calculate CMG"" button completes the CMG calculation." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Pressing the ""Clear"" button clears the input and output data." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  Distances are rounded to the nearest hundredth of a nautical mile.  Times are rounded to the nearest minute.  Courses are " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rounded to the nearest degree.  Latitudes and longitudes are rounded to the nearest tenth of a minute." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
