		Me.txtHelpMoBoard.Text = "MANEUVERING BOARD (MoBoard)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  Perform several of the calculations typically done on a maneuvering board.  Calculate the Closest Point of Approach (CPA) of two vessels, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "course and speed of a contact (target) vessel, and related information.  Vessel 1 is the reference vessel (you).  Vessel 2 is the contact vessel.  Ranges " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and bearings are measured from Vessel 1 to Vessel 2.  If the resulting CPA is zero, a collision will occur.  (It is up to the captain to determine what range " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is ""close enough"".  Two types of calculations are included, depending on what data is known.  On a recreational vessel, data is typically obtained from a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "radar without Automatic Radar Plotting Aid (ARPA)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Calculate the speed and direction of the true wind if the speed and course of the vessel and the speed and relative direction of the apparent wind are " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "known.  Calculate the speed and relative direction of the apparent wind if the speed and course of the vessel and the speed and  direction of the true " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "wind are known." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:  In the first (default) CPA type of calculation, required inputs are the range and bearing from Vessel 1 to Vessel 2 at two times, and, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "optionally, the course and speed of Vessel 1 (only needed to calculate Vessel 2 course and speed, not needed for CPA).  (In practice, a minimum of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "three sets of measurements are taken, in order verify that Vessel 2 is maintaining its course and speed.  Once verified, any two of the sets of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "measurements, preferably the earliest and latest, can be used for the calculation.)  Times are in whole minutes, ranges to hundredths of a nautical mile " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(limited to 99.99), bearings to tenths of a degree (limited to 359.9), course to tenths of a degree (limited to 359.9), and speed to tenths of a knot " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(limited to (99.9).  Press the ""Calculate"" button.  Outputs are the range of the CPA; the time to the CPA (measured from the later time); the bearing " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "from Vessel 1 to Vessel 2 at the CPA; the time of CPA;  the direction of relative movement (DRM, also called direction of relative motion) and the speed " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of relative movement (SRM, also called speed of relative motion) of Vessel 2 with respect to Vessel 1; and the course and speed of Vessel 2.  (SRM and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "DRM are the speed and course of Vessel 2 with respect to Vessel 1, and can be thought of as the speed and course of Vessel 2 if Vessel 1 were " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "stationary.)  Vessel 2 can be a fixed object.  If no values are entered for  Vessel 1 speed, Vessel 1 is considered stationary.  If the time to the CPA is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "negative, CPA occurred before the later time, and the vessels are already moving apart." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If the second time appears to be earlier than the first time, verification that the second time is on the following day, i.e. after midnight, will be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "requested, to confirm that it is not just an input error." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "In the second type of CPA calculation, required inputs the speeds and courses of Vessel 1 and Vessel 2, and the bearing and range from Vessel 1 to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Vessel 2 at any available time.  (Actual time is not required.)  Speeds are to tenths of a knot (limited to 99.9), courses and bearings are to tenths of a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "degree, and ranges are to hundredths of a nautical mile (limited to 99.99).   Press the ""Calculate"" button.  Outputs are the range of the CPA; the time " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to the CPA (from the time of the data); the bearing from Vessel 1 to Vessel 2 at the CPA; and the DRM  and SRM." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For the CPA calculations. course and bearing inputs can be true (recommended) or magnetic or compass (with respect to Vessel 1's compass), but must " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "be consistent throughout, with resulting outputs of the same type." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For the True Wind calculation, required inputs are the true course and speed of the vessel and the speed and relative ""from"" direction of the apparent " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "wind.  Courses and directions are to tenths of a degree (limited to 359.9).  Speeds are to tenths of a knot (limited to 99.9).  The relative direction of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "apparent wind can be entered as a negative number.  For instance, if the apparent wind is coming from 50° off the port bow, this can be entered as " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "310° (360 - 50) or -50° (relative).  The calculated direction of the true wind is displayed in degrees true.  However, if the Vessel Course is omitted or set" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to zero, the calculated direction of the true wind is effectively in degrees relative." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For the Apparent Wind calculation, required inputs are the true course and speed of the vessel and the speed and true (referred to true north) ""from"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "direction of the true wind.  Courses and directions are to tenths of a degree (limited to 359.9).  Speeds are to tenths of a knot (limited to 99.9).    The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculated direction of the apparent wind is displayed in degrees relative (to the course of the vessel).  However, if the Vessel Course is omitted or set" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to zero, the calculated direction of the apparent wind is effectively in degrees true." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Pressing the ""Clear"" button clears the input data of the displayed type of calculation, unless an illegal value remains, which must be corrected first.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Inputs of the types that are not displayed are not cleared." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Switching from one type to the other clears the output data but does not clear the input data." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Calculations assume that both vessels have maintained course and speed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  As with a maneuvering board, these are two-dimensional approximate solutions to a three-dimensional problem, but should be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "reasonably accurate for values for which a maneuvering board would be used.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Ranges are displayed to hundredths of a nautical mile, elapsed times to tenths of minutes, clock times to whole minutes, speeds to tenths of a knot, and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "courses and bearings to tenths of a degree." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
