		Me.txtHelpYellow.Text = "YELLOW PAGES (INCREMENTS AND CORRECTIONS)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  Reproduces the values of the Nautical Almanac Increments and Corrections table, traditionally known as the ""yellow pages"" because of their " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "color in the government edition.  Can be entered ""forwards"" or ""backwards"".  When entering ""forwards"", calculates GHA Increment for Sun/Planets, Aries, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and Moon, given UT minutes and seconds; calculates v or d correction given UT minutes and v or d value.  When entering ""backwards"", calculates time " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "given a GHA Increment for Sun/Planets, Aries, and Moon." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The sole intent of this tool is to help the student avoid making errors, or to help find errors already made, in using the Nautical Almanac Increments and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Corrections table, for instance the common ""right page, wrong column"" problem.  It does this by presenting output data for a single set of input values, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "instead of the full-page format of the Nautical Almanac." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation: Select whether to enter the table ""forwards"" (default) or ""backwards""." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """Forwards"" mode is typically used when extracting data from the Nautical Almanac for a sight reduction.  To calculate the GHA Increment, enter the UT " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "minutes and seconds, and select whether to obtain the increment for Sun/Planets, Aries, or Moon.  To calculate the v or d correction, enter the UT minutes " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and the v or d value from the daily pages of the nautical Almanac, without a sign.  The GHA Increment and v or d correction will be displayed and will be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "automatically updated for whatever data is currently entered." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """Backwards"" mode can be used as part of the GHA method of finding the time of meridian transit.  Select whether to use Sun/Planets, Aries, or Moon.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Most common would be Sun, in determining the time of Local Apparent Noon.)  Enter the degrees and minutes of the GHA Increment (limited to 15°0.00' " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "for Sun/Planets, 15°02.5' for Aries, 14°19.0' for Moon).  The corresponding time will be displayed, and will be automatically updated for whatever data is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "currently entered." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Both ""Forwards"" and ""Backwards"" have no default object (i.e.  Sun/Planets, Aries, or Moon).  In order to avoid a chance of error, an object must be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "selected." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  Although all 21960 possible values of Increments and Corrections in the ""forwards"" mode have not been compared to those in the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Nautical Almanac, it is believed that they all match.  Since the formulas for the values are published, but the method of rounding in the Nautical Almanac is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "unknown, the accuracy of the Yellow Pages Increment and Correction values will be specified as 0.1'.  In the ""backwards"" mode, times are rounded to the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "nearest second  (rounded up if the GHA Increment is exactly between two tabulated values) and should match well." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Contrary to common belief, not all Increments and Corrections tables are identical.  In 2001, four of the 10800 correction values changed, and are " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "expected to remain with their new values in the future.  Specifically these are:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	minute	v or d	Corr (pre-2001)	Corr (2001 and later)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	   22            2.8                1.1                              1.0" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	   22           16.4               6.2                              6.1" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "   	   52            9.2                8.1                              8.0" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	   52           16.4             14.4                            14.3" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Celestial Tools will show both values for these four cases." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
