		Me.txtHelpDistances.Text = "DISTANCES" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  Calculate the distance to the natural horizon (Bowditch 2002 Table 12).  Calculate the geographical range of visibility (the maximum " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "distance an object can be seen) (Bowditch 2002 Table 13).  These values are a function of height of eye, the height of the object, and the curvature of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the earth, and not the clarity of the atmosphere, quality of illumination, etc." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Calculate the distance to an object based on a measured vertical angle by three methods:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "1) Distance by Vertical Angle Measured Between Waterline at Object and Top of Object (Bowditch 2002 Table 16):  Calulates the distance to an object " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of known height above sea level lying within the observer's visible horizon." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "2) Distance by Vertical Angle Measured Between Waterline at Object and Sea Horizon Beyond Object (Bowditch 2002 Table 17):  Calculates the distance " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to an object lying within or short of the horizon when the height of eye of the observer is known." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "3) Distance by Vertical Angle Measured Between Sea Horizon and Top of Object Beyond Sea Horizon (Bowditch 2002 Table 15):  Calculates the distance " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to an object of known height above sea level when the object lies beyond the horizon." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Vertical angles are typically measured with a sextant." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:  Select the desired function.  Boxes for only the required inputs will appear." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For all calculators, Height of Eye (HE) can be entered in feet, meters, inches, or centimeters.  Height of Object can be entered in feet or meters. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Heights are limited to four characters, including a decimal point.  (The maximum value of Height of Object in the tables is 984 feet or 300 meters in Table " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "13.  The maximum value of Height of Eye in the tables is 820 feet or about 250 meters in Table 12.  Table 15 allows up to 2000 feet for the difference " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "between the Height of Object and Height of Eye.  Older editions of Bowditch had heights of eye up to 10000 feet.)  All heights of eye and heights of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "objects are above the waterline.  Note that most published lists show heights referred to mean high water.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Distance of the Horizon:  Enter the HE value and unit.  Press the ""Calculate"" button, and the distance to the natural horizon will be displayed in nautical " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "miles (nm) and statute miles (mi).  (One application of the distance to the natural horizon would be to determine whether an island obscures the natural " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "horizon when checking the available azimuth range of a new ""Favorite Place"" on a chart.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Geographical Range of Visibility:  Enter the HE value and unit and the height of object value and unit.  Press the ""Calculate"" button, and the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "geographical range of visibility will be displayed in nautical miles (nm) and a statute miles (mi)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For all Distance by Vertical Angle calculators, the uncorrected vertical angle, hs, is the vertical angle measured with a sextant before correcting for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "index error and dip.  hs and index error (IE) can be entered in either degrees and decimal minutes (DM.m) or degrees, minutes, and seconds (DMS).  hs " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is limited to 89º59.9' or 89º59'59"".  (These values far exceed practical use, but are allowed for academic reasons.)  Corrected altitude is limited to 90º.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(The maximum value in the tables is 30º in Table 15.)  Off the arc index error can be entered as either the actual reading from the sextant (""off the arc " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(rdg.)"") or the calculated value (""off the arc (val.)""); the program makes the appropriate adjustment when calculating index correction.  (Take, for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "example, an arc reading between 1 and 2 degrees and a micrometer drum reading of 22.3 minutes.  This can be entered as either 2°22.3' off the arc " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(rdg.) or as 1°37.7' off the arc (val.).  Either will give an index correction of +1°37.7.) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Distance by Vertical Angle Measured Between Waterline at Object and Top of Object:  Enter the HE value and unit.  Enter hs and IE.  Press the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """Calculate"" button, and the distance to object will be displayed in nautical miles (nm) and statute miles (mi)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Distance by Vertical Angle Measured Between Waterline at Object and Sea Horizon Beyond Object:  Enter the HE value and unit.  Enter hs and IE.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Press the ""Calculate"" button, and the distance to object will be displayed in yards, nautical miles (nm), and statute miles (mi).  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Distance by Vertical Angle Measured Between Sea Horizon and Top of Object Beyond Sea Horizon:  Enter the HE value and unit and the height of object " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "value and unit.  Enter hs and IE.  Press the ""Calculate"" button, and the distance to object will be displayed in nautical miles (nm) and a statute miles (mi)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For all Distance by Vertical Angle calculators, the Corrected Altitude (measured sextant altitude, hs, corrected for index error and dip, where " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "appropriate) will also be shown, for use as an entering argument in comparing results with the Bowditch tables." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  Distance to natural horizon and geographical range of visibility are rounded to tenths of a mile (nautical or statute)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Distance by Vertical Angle Measured Between Waterline at Object and Top of Object:  This calculator provides the solution of a plane right triangle " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "having its right angle at the base of the observed object and its altitude coincident with the vertical dimension of the observed object.  It is based on " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the following simplifying assumptions:  (1) height of eye is zero; (2) the sea surface between the observer and the object is flat; (3) atmospheric " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "refraction is negligible; (4) the waterline at the object is vertically below the peak of the object.  The error due to the height of eye of the observer " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "does not exceed 3% of the distance off for sextant angles less than 20º and heights of eye less than 1/3 of the object height.  The error due to the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "waterline not being below the peak of the object does not exceed 3% of the distance off when the height of eye is less than 1/3 of the object height" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and the offset of the waterline from the base of the object is less than 1/10 of the distance off.  Errors due to the earth's curvature and atmospheric " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "refraction are negligible for cases of practical interest.  Distance is rounded to hundredths of a mile (nautical or statute)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Distance by Vertical Angle Measured Between Waterline at Object and Sea Horizon Beyond Object:  This calculator corrects the measured angle (hs) for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "index error.  An average value of terrestrial refraction and the mean radius of the earth are used.  Distance is rounded to whole yards and hundredths " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of a mile (nautical or statute)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Distance by Vertical Angle Measured Between Sea Horizon and Top of Object Beyond Sea Horizon:  This calculator corrects the measured angle (hs) for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "index error and dip.  It uses the standard value refraction.  An error may be introduced if standard refraction does not apply due to non-standard " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "temperature and atmospheric pressure.  Distance is rounded to tenths of a mile (nautical or statute)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Because of the vagaries of rounding, the output of Celestial Tools may not precisely match the Bowditch tables." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
