			"THE SAILINGS" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  For Mid-Latitude Sailing, Mercator Sailing, and ""Accurate Rhumb Line"" Sailing:  Calculate course and distance given initial position and final " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "position.  Calculate final position given initial position, course, and distance.  Calculate set and drift given DR position, fix position, and elapsed time from " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "previous fix; if previous fix is known, calculate drift angle, distance between fixes, course made good (more properly called track made good), speed " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "made good.  For Great Circle Sailing:  Calculate initial course and distance, maximum latitude (vertex), and final course, given initial position and final " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "position.  Calculate final position, maximum latitude, and final course, given initial position, initial course, and distance.  Calculate the points on a great " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "circle route, rhumb line course and distance from point to point, and total rhumb line distance.  For all Sailings:  Calculate position given range and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "bearing to known object." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "This tool includes three types of rhumb line sailings, Mid-Latitude, Mercator, and ""Accurate Rhumb Line"", and Great Circle sailing." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Mid-Latitude Sailing is a form of plane sailing, where the surface of the Earth is considered flat and the curvature of the Earth is not taken into account.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "It is an approximation that is considered sufficiently accurate for shorter distances.  This value varies from source to source, with some sources " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "suggesting no more than 600 nm, and others, e.g. Bowditch, having examples over 1000 nm.  Earlier versions of Celestial Tools limited this distance to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "600 nm, but this limitation was increased to 9999.9 nm with V2.2.0, allowing a comparison of this method to the other methods provided for longer " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "distances.  (This limitation only applies to input values; calculated distances can exceed this.)  However, mid-latitude sailing has its issues near the poles, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "so the maximum latitude is limited  to 84°59.9', and a message will be generated if any part of the course exceeds this.  (Note that this will also generate " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the message for a course of 0° or 180° which exceeds this latitude, for which mid-latitude sailing is accurate, but for which there is no need to use a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sailing of any kind." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Mercator sailing considers the curvature of the earth, and is considered the most accurate form of rhumb line sailing developed for tabular use, but is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "less popular than mid-latitude sailing because its manual calculation is more difficult and requires an additional table (meridional parts).  USPS considers it " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the preferred tabular rhumb line method for distances over 600 nm.  As with mid-latitude, input distance is limited to 9999.9 nm, but calculated distances " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "can exceed this.  When using tables, Mercator sailing is unreliable when the course lies within 5° of due east or west.  This is not a problem when using " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a calculator or computer except when calculating final position when the course is directly east or west, where conventional mid-latitude sailing is used." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """Accurate Rhumb Line"" sailing is the method used in Visual Passage Planner 2, and was never a tabular method.  It is the most accurate form of rhumb " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "line sailing, and can be used for short or long distances." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For Mercator sailing and Accurate Rhumb Line sailing, for courses of 0° or 180° where the course crosses a pole, the calculation will not be completed, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "but a message will be generated." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Although most similar to Mid-Latitude Sailing, the Destination L and Lo function of any of the rhumb line sailings can be used in place of the ""Simplified " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Traverse Table"", with more accurate results.  However, starting with V5.0.0, the Simplified Traverse Table computation of arrival position knowing " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "departure point and distance traveled has been included." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Any of the rhumb line sailings can be used to calculate the drift angle between two fixes by calculating the course from the earlier fix to the later fix and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the course between the earlier fix and the DR position at the time of the later fix, and taking the difference between them.  Alternatively, the drift " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "angle can be found in one step by using the set and drift tool." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Great circle sailing provides the shortest distance between two points, but since it is more difficult to follow a great circle route than a rhumb line, it is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "most practical when traveling long distances at high latitudes.  A frequently used rule of thumb is that for latitudes less than 40° and distances less than " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "1000 nautical miles, the distance saving in a great circle route is usually not significant." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "A great circle route can reach latitudes higher than that of the point of departure or destination.  To avoid high latitudes where ice or gales might be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "encountered, a modification of great circle sailing called ""composite sailing"" may be used.  There are two methods used to accomplish this.  In Method 1, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a great circle route is plotted from the point of departure to the destination and is followed from the point of departure until it crosses the limiting " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "latitude, then the parallel of the limiting latitude is followed until the great circle again crosses it, then the great circle route is followed to the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "destination.  In Method 2, one great circle is plotted from the point of departure tangent to the limiting parallel, and a second from the destination " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "tangent to the limiting parallel.  The first is followed from the point of departure to the limiting latitude, then the parallel of the limiting latitude is followed " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "until the second great circle reaches it, then the second great circle is sailed to the destination.  Method 1 is easier to plot, but Method 2 results in a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "shorter course.  (In both methods, plotting is done on a gnomonic projection.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For all cases, press ""Calculate"" to complete the calculation.  (See below regarding the ""Simplified Traverse Table"" method.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Mid-Latitude, Mercator, and ""Accurate Rhumb Line"" Sailing:  Select whether you want to calculate course and distance, final position (destination L and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Lo), or set and drift.  L1 and Lo1 are the latitude and longitude of the initial (point of departure) position.  L2 and Lo2 are the latitude and longitude of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the final (destination) position.  L1 and L2 are limited to 84°59.9' for Mid-Latitude,and  89°59.9' for Mercator and ""Accurate Rhumb Line""." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When calculating final position, enter L1, Lo1, true course (with 0.1° resolution), and either the distance (as actual distance or as start and end " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "knotmeter log values, Log1 and Log2, limited to 9999.9nm) or the speed and running time (as actual running time or start and end times, Time1 and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Time2, in hhmm format).  Distance can be entered with tenth of a nautical mile resolution up to 9999.9 nautical miles. Speed can be entered with tenth " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of a knot resolution up to 99.9 knots.  (The speed value is either a constant speed or average speed based on the actual conditions.)  Run Time can be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "entered in integer hours and integer minutes, or just integer minutes.  If an hour value is entered, minutes are limited to 59.  If no (or zero) hour value " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is entered, minutes are limited to 999 (almost 17 hours).  If a minute value greater than 59 is entered, the hour box is disabled.  If Log1 is greater than " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Log2 an error message will be generated.  If Time1 is later than Time2 an error message will be generated.  (The program does not consider this to be a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "run that crosses midnight.  If this is actually the case, it is best to use Run Time.)  Press the ""Calculate"" button to get the latitude and longitude of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "final position.  If speed and time were entered, calculated distance will also be displayed.  If Time1 and Time2 were entered, calculated run time will also " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "be displayed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If Mid-Latitude and Destination L and Lo are both selected, there is the option of calculation the arrival (destination) position using the ""Simplified " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Traverse Table"" method taught in recent N courses, rather than the more accurate mid-latitude calculation.  If this is chosen, outputs consist of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "eight lines of intermediate values, the Arrival Position answer, and any other calculation that is normally displayed if distance is not input directly.  Only " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the final result of the intermediate values is shown - how they are derived is not, as that can be seen on the worksheet.  ""Use this mid-latitude for CLS " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "SAPS plot"", described below, is ignored even if checked.  As with Mid-Latitude sailing, L1 is limited to 84°59.9'." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When calculating course and distance, enter L1, Lo1, L2, and Lo2, then press the ""Calculate"" button." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When calculating set, drift, and drift angle, enter the Fix L and Fix Lo and the DR L and DR Lo at the time of the fix.  For drift determination, enter the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "elapsed time from the previous fix in integer hours and integer minutes, or just integer minutes, or the times of the earlier and later fixes, Time1 and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Time2, in hhmm format.  (The same rules as when calculating final position apply.)  (Time is not required for set or drift angle determination.)  If the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "latitude and longitude of the prior fix are available, check the ""Prior fix available for drift angle, CMG, SMG calculation"" and enter the values (latitude " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "limited to 89°59.9').  Press ""Calculate"" to get the set, total drift (the distance between the DR and the fix), drift, and, if the prior fix location was " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "entered, the drift angle and whether it is to port or to starboard, the distance beween fixes, the course made good (CMG), and the speed made good " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(SMG).  If Time1 and Time2 were entered, calculated run time will also be displayed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Set and drift can also be determined between two fixes by first determining the Destination L and Lo from the first fix knowing course and speed.  Then " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "use this position as the DR L and DR Lo, along with the L and Lo of the second fix, in the Set and Drift calculation.  Including the first fix as the ""prior fix"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "will also provide drift angle.  The need to do this, however, was eliminated in V5.4.0, as these values have been included in the calculation.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If Mercator Sailing is being used, the meridional parts for the starting latitude (M1), the destination latitude (M2), and the meridional difference (m) will " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "also be displayed, unless calculating final position with a course directly east or west, where conventional mid-latitude sailing is used.  Two options are " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "available:  ""WGS 1972 ellipsoid"" or ""Clarke 1866 spheroid"".  With ""WGS 1972 ellipsoid"" selected, the values of the meridional parts should agree with the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Meridional Parts tables of editions of Bowditch (American Pratical Navigator) starting in the late 1900s.  If ""Clarke 1866 spheroid"" is selected, the values " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of the meridional parts should agree with the Meridional Parts tables of editions of Bowditch of the mid-1900s.  The values in the Meridional Parts tables " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of editions of Bowditch can be produced by just entering a latitude and pressing ""Calculate""." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When calculating final position or set and drift, as any value is entered, values that are no longer appropriate are disabled.  For example, when " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculating final position, if Time1 is entered, Run Time, Log1, Log2, and Distance will be disabled." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Normally mid-latitude sailing uses the algebraic average of the initial latitude and the final latitude (whether an input or calculated) (south latitude is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "negative).  However, when using a Constant Latitude Scale (CLS) Small Area Plotting Sheet (SAPS), it is often desirable to use a convenient value of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "mid-latitude in order to keep the plot near the center of the sheet.  If a specific mid-latitude is to be used, check the ""Use this mid-latitude for CLS SAPS " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "plot"" checkbox and enter the desired value in degrees and tens of minutes (0, 10, 20, 30, 40, or 50), with a maximum value of  55°00', the largest " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "value shown on the CLS SAPS. This will result in an output that more closely matches the plot, but causes a slight error in longitude, zero at the equator " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and increasing to about 0.8' at a latitude of 55°.  Since a CLS SAPS has latitude and longitude ranges of one degree, an error message will appear if " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "either is exceeded.  If the selected mid-latitude causes the latitude range of the CLS SAPS to exceed one degree an error message will appear.  (The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Universal Plotting Sheet is also a CLS chart, bit its small scale does not warrant the use of this feature.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When switching from one sailing to another, outputs are cleared but inputs are retained for ease in making comparisons.  When switching from one " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "function to another, all inputs and outputs are cleared.  Pressing ""Clear All"" removes all the input and output data.  Pressing ""Clear But Use L2, Lo2 For " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "New L1, Lo1"" removes all the input and output data but makes the entered or calculated final position into a new initial position, and, if a specific " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "mid-latitude was entered and the box checked, the entered value will be retained and the box will remain checked." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Keep in mind that, because of rounding, the Destination L and Lo and the Course and Distance calculations might give slghtly inconsistent results.  For " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "instance, if you enter the latitudes and longitudes of a departure point and a destination point and calculate the course and distance, and then use the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculated values in a Destination L and Lo calculation with the same departure point, you will probably not end up with exactly the same destination " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "point." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Great Circle Sailing:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Select whether you want to calculate initial course and distance or final position (destination L and Lo).  L1 and Lo1 are the latitude and longitude of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "initial (point of departure) position.  L2 and Lo2 are the latitude and longitude of the final (destination) position." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When calculating initial course and distance, enter L1, Lo1, L2, and Lo2.  Press the ""Calculate"" button and the initial course, distance, maximum latitude, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and final course will be displayed.  If the initial and final points are antipodes (i.e. on diametrically opposite sides of the earth) but not the poles, a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "message will be displayed.  (If  L1 and/or L2 are poles, the values of Lo1 and Lo2 do not matter.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When calculating final position, enter L1, Lo1, true course (with 0.1° resolution), and  distance.  Distance can be entered with tenth of a nautical mile " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "resolution up to 9999.9 nautical miles.  Press the ""Calculate"" button to get the latitude and longitude of the final position, maximum latitude, and final " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "course." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note that the initial course for the reversed course (L2, Lo2 to L1, Lo1) equals the final course of the original course +/-180°." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "After the ""Calculate"" button is pressed, and if the entered or calculated course is not 0° or 180°, another button, ""Points on Great Circle Route"", " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "becomes enabled.  When it is pressed, another window, ""Points on Great Circle Route"",  opens, listing the latitudes for the initial and final longitudes for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the great circle course, the latitudes for each whole 5° longitude between them, the rhumb line course and distance from point to point, and the total " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rhumb line distance.  (The program uses ""Accurate Rhumb Line"" sailing to calculate the courses and distances, but any rhumb line tool  can now be used " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to calculate a rhumb line course between individual points.  The ""Points on Great Circle Route"" window also allows the calculation of the latitude for any " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "longitude on that great circle, not just longitudes on the route.  Enter the longitude of the point, press the ""Point Latitude"" button, and the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "corresponding latitude will be displayed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Once any data, input or output, is displayed on the ""Points on Great Circle Route"" window, it is cleared whenever the ""Calculate"" button is pressed " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "again." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Composite Sailing:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When Great Circle, Initial Course and Distance is selected, and it is desired to use composite sailing, check the ""Use Composite Sailing"" check box.  Enter " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the latitude limit (range 1° to 89°59.9'); in practice, typically 38° to 50°).  Select Method 1 or Method 2.  Activate the ""Calculate"" button to complete the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculation.  Outputs include initial course, longitudes of the limiting parallel crossings, the distance of each segment, the total distance, and the final " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "course." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Pressing the ""Points on Composite Route"" button performs a function similar to the ""Points on Great Circle Route"" button for the particular composite " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sailing method selected., except the portion along the limiting parallel is shown as one segment rather than being broken at whole 5° longitude " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "increments.   If Method 1 is selected, the ""Points on Composite Route"" window also allows the calculation of the latitude for any longitude on the great " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "circle portion of the route (including the portion beyond the limiting parallel), not just longitudes on the route.  Enter the longitude of the point, press the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """Point Latitude"" button, and the corresponding latitude will be displayed.  (Because there are two great circles onvolved in Method 2, this feature is only " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "enabled for Method 1.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Pressing ""Clear All"" removes all the input and output data.  Pressing ""Clear But Use L2, Lo2 For New L1, Lo1"" removes all the input and outpur data but " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "makes the entered or calculated final position into a new initial position.  This allows the final postiion of a vessel that has traveled a series of rhumb " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "lines to be determined mathematically, a convenient, step-by-step version of the Bowditch 2002 Table 4 Traverse Table method." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Other applications:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The LoC/NASR tool will calculate an EP for a Law of Cosines reduction and an AP/EP (as defined in the LoC/NASR Help) for a NASR reduction, but this " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "can also be done with the Mid-Latitude and Mercator sailings, using the ""Calculate Destination L and Lo"" function.  Enter the DR L and Lo (LoC) or AP L " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and Lo (NASR) as L1 and L2, intercept length as Distance, and azimuth (be sure to add or subtract 180º if intercept was Away) as True Course.  The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "resulting L2 and Lo2 correspond to the EP (LoC) or AP/EP (NASR)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Any of the Sailings can be used to calculate position given the range and bearing to an object with a known latitude and longitude.  Use the ""Calculate " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Destination L and Lo"" function, with the latitude and longitude of the object as L1 and Lo1, and the reciprocal true bearing for True Course.  After the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "distance is entered, press the Calculate button to get your latitude and longitude.  Since visual bearings are generally at distances no more than 10 nm, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "any of the Sailings should give the same position." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Taking this a step further, consider the situation of a multi-body fix using the NASR method from a moving vessel, where an earlier LOP must be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "advanced to the last LOP.  Enter the AP L and Lo (as L1 and Lo1), speed, and elapsed time from the earlier sight to the last sight.  The resulting L2 and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Lo2 effectively advance the AP to the time of the last sight.  Use the ""Clear But Use L2, Lo2 for New L1, Lo1"" button.  Then enter intercept length as " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Distance and azimuth (be sure to add or subtract 180º if intercept was Away) as True Course.  The resulting L2 and Lo2 correspond to the advanced " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "AP/EP." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The Sailings can also be used to find the set and drift of current using two fixes and the course, speed, and run time between them  (or the time of each " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "fix).  Use the ""Calculate Destination L and Lo"" function with the first fix, course, speed, and elapsed time.   (Be sure to record the Destination L and Lo, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "as they are not saved when switching functions.)  Enter the calculated position as the DR position in the ""Calculate Set and Drift"" function, the second " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "fix as the Fix position, and the run time between them (or the time of each fix)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  Calculated courses are displayed to both the nearest hundredth of a degree and rounded to whole degrees (just to whole " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "degrees for the rhumb line courses in ""Points on Great Circle Route"").  Calculated distances and total drift are displayed to the nearest tenth of a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "nautical mile.  Calculated set and drift angle are displayed to the nearest degree.  Calculated drift is displayed to the nearest tenth of a knot.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Calculated latitudes and longitudes are displayed to the nearest tenth of a minute." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Rhumb line distances in ""Points on Great Circle Route"" may differ by 0.1 nm from that shown using ""Accurate Rhumb Line"" on an individual pair of points " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "because ""Points on Great Circle Route"" uses the unrounded calculated values of latitude." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For Mercator sailing, values of meridional parts for latitudes with whole minutes (the latitudes tabulated in the Meridional Parts tables) are expected to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "agree with the Meridional Parts tables of editions of Bowditch (American Practial Navigator) from at least 1981 through 2002 when ""WGS 1972 ellipsoid"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is selected.  These tables are based on the World Geodetic Survey of 1972 ellipsoid.  (This is the table that was used in the USPS JN course in the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "1990s.)  When ""Clarke 1866 spheroid"" is selected, values of meridional parts are expected to agree with the Meridional Parts tables of editions of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "mid-20th century, which are based on the Clarke spheroid of 1866, the standard reference spheroid used for charting North America at the time.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Editions of the early 20th century and earlier used yet another basis.)  When a latitude of interest contains tenths of minutes, manual calculation is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "done by linear interpolation between the whole minute latitudes immediately above and below the latitude of interest.  Celestial Tools calculates the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "meridional parts for latitudes with tenths of minutes using the same formulas that are used to calculate the values for latitudes with whole minutes.  This " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is more accurate than interpolation, but could result in a differences compared to interpolated values.  The differene between calculated and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "interpolated values increases with increasing latitude, being nor more than 0.1 at low to middle latitudes, no more than 0.2 up to about 89°, and as " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "much as 0.7% (over 200) near 90°" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For composite sailing Method 1, because of the rounding of the rhumb line distances, it is possible that the total rhumb line distance could be slightly less " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "than the total composite sailing distance." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Remember that for all sailings, calculations are done to the full precision of the computer, followed by rounding.  In most cases this results in an answer " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "that is different, and probably more accurate, than a calculation done by hand with tables.  As with tables, the computations assume the Earth is a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sphere, not an oblate spheroid.  For this reason, results may be slightly different than those of sources that consider the oblateness." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
