		Me.txtHelpAveraging.Text = "SIGHT AVERAGING" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  To analyze and obtain the average watch times and sextant altitudes for a run of sights." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:  Input up to ten pairs of watch times (WT) and sextant altitudes (hs).  Sextant altitudes can be entered in either degrees and decimal " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "minutes (DM.m) or degrees, minutes, and seconds (DMS).  Watch times must be entered in chronological order.  Subsequent data entry lines do not " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "become active until an acceptable time is entered on the current line.  (This allows all the watch times to be entered as a group, all the sextant altitude " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "degrees to be entered as a group, etc.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Once data is entered on a line, it can be changed, but a line of data should never be completely deleted.  This will result in error messages.  If, for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "instance, you wish to eliminate a sight from averaging, use the Analyze function described below.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "At this point either the ""Analyze"" button or the ""Calculate Averages"" button can be activated." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If you are happy with the data as entered, activate the ""Calculate Averages"" button and the average watch time and average sextant altitude will be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "displayed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "However, if you want to examine the data to look for bad sights or erroneous entries, activate the ""Analyze"" button.  Unless the body is near the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "observer's meridian, a number of observations taken in quick succession and plotted versus time should result in nearly a straight line.  When the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """Analyze"" button is activated, the values of the ""residuals"" for each sight are then displayed.  The residuals are the differences, in arc-minutes, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "between the measured altitude entered and the altitude calculated by a least-squares linear regression fit determined from using all the entered times " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and altitudes.  (In versions of Celestial Tools previous to V5.1.1, the differences (from sight to sight) of watch time and sextant altitude are displayed, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "plus the rate of change of sextant altitude per unit time.  It was often difficult to determine which sight was an outlier.)  If a sight seems bad, having a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "particularly high residual (ignoring the sign), and you do not want to include it in the averaging, clear its check box. If data was entered incorrectly, it " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "can be fixed now.   (Whenever the ""Analyze"" button is pressed, all the check boxes will be checked, even if previously cleared, and the displayed " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "averages will disappear.  It is presumed that a subsequent press of the ""Analyze"" button was done because of a change in the data, perhaps from an " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "erroneous value, so the old averages are no longer valid.)  Then press the ""Calculate Averages"" button and the averages for the checked sights will be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "displayed.  If, for any reason, a sight that is intended to be used for the average does not have a check box, simply press the ""Analyze"" button again.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Note that this method of analysis results in a line through the data points that should resemble a line drawn by eye on a plot, but can result in a good " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sight being rejected and a bad sight being retained.  See the article ""How to Average Celestial Sights for Optimum Accuracy"", by David Burch, for an " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "improved method.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note that although the watch times have to be entered in chronological order, if you do not intend to analyze the sights the sextant altitudes do not " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "have to be entered on the same line as the corresponding time.  However, it is recommended that the watch times and sextant altitudes be entered as " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "pairs.  If you intend to analyze the sights, it is mandatory that they be entered as pairs.  In any case, an error message is generated if the number of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "watch times does not equal the number of sextant altitudes." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If a run of sights crosses midnight, which could occur when using an artificial horizon, the watch times after midnight must be entered with an hour value " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of 24 instead of 00.  (Note that only this tool allows times of up to 245959 to be entered.)  If necessary, subtract 24 hours from the resulting average " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "watch time and add one day." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  Average watch time is displayed to the nearest second.  Average sextant altitude is displayed to the nearest tenth of a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "minute.  ""Scatter"" values are displayed to the nearest tenth of an arc-minute." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
