			"SIGHT REDUCTION METHODS & FIX" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  Allows data extracted from the Nautical Almanac (rather than from the built-in medium-precision almanac) to be entered for sight " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "reductions using various methods.  (In keeping with the spirit of Celestial Tools as being an instructional aid rather than doing the work for the student, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "this module is  intended, for most methods, to be only a little more than Windows executable versions of DOS programs and spreadsheets already " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "available on the USPS web site.)  The methods included are the Law of Cosines (LoC) calculator method, the Nautical Almanac Concise method (NASR), " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Pub. 249 (formerly H.O. 249, Sight Reduction Tables for Air Navigation, A.P. 3270 in the United Kingdom), Pub. 229 (formerly H.O. 229, Sight Reduction " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Tables for Marine Navigation, H.D. 486 in the United Kingdom), H.O. 214 (Tables of Computed Altitude and Azimuth), H.O. 211 (Dead Reckoning " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Altitude and Azimuth Table, Third Edition, known as Ageton, and the Modified H.O. 211 Compact Sight Reduction Table, known as Ageton-Bayless), " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "H.O. 208 (Navigation Tables for Mariners and Aviators, Sixth Edition, known as Dreisonstok), two versions of the S-Table, and the Weems Line of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Position Book." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Over the years the USPS SR forms for the same sight reduction method have changed in their layout, operation, and Zn resolution.  Celestial Tools SR " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """forms"" are patterned after the following USPS SR forms:  Law of Cosines - SR 96a; NASR - SR 96a; Pub. 249 - SR Pub. 249 Vol II & III; Pub. 229 - SR " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "96b; H.O. 211 - SR 87, with the exception regarding Zn noted in Accuracy/Resolution.  The form for H.O. 214 is patterned as a combination of the H.O. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "214 form of SR 712 and the Pub. 229 form of SR 96b.  The form for H.O. 208 is patterned after the examples in the sixth edition of the H.O. 208 book.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Calculates an Estimated Position (EP) for all methods. Calculates an AP/EP and a DR-LOP distance for all methods that use an Assumed Position (AP) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rather than a Dead Reckoning (DR) position.  (See below for how EP and AP/EP are defined.)  Use two more sights reduced by the Law of Cosines " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "method to establish a fix." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:  Required inputs are GHA or LHA (Tot GHA or LHA from SR form), declination (Dec from SR form), observed altitude (Ho from SR form), " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and DR latitude and longitude (if GHA is being used).  To use LHA instead of GHA, enter LHA in place of GHA and set DR Lo to zero or leave blank.  (Be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "aware that doing this will give an EP, and an AP/EP if applicable, referred to 0° longitude.)  Time is only required if it is intended to establish a fix from a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "moving vessel.  (The time value need not be accurate.  It is only used to determine which is the latest of the selected sights so the earlier sights can be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "advanced to its DR position.)  Select one of the eight sight reduction method buttons and the corresponding sight reduction will be displayed in the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "format required by the SR form (where the format of the form is known)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "GHA has an upper limit of 719°59.9' in case Tot GHA from the SR form exceeds 360° and has not been adjusted." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The NASR method is not suitable for values of Ho exceeding 75°.  The Law of Cosines is not suitable for values of Ho exceeding 88°.  Pub. 229 requires " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a special interpolation technique for Ho values of 86° or greater that is not included in this program. The corresponding buttons will be disabled if the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "entered value of Ho exceeds these limits.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Ho has a lower limit of -59.9', so sights on bodies on the visible horizon (with a negative altitude on the celestial horizon) and heights of eye up to about " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "75 feet can be reduced.  If a negative value of minutes of Ho is entered, any value of degrees of Ho will be cleared and the Ho degrees box will be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "disabled." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When using the standard procedure for determining Asm Lo and Asm LHA with the NASR method, if the difference between Asm Lo and DR Lo is exactly " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "30', there are two possible correct sets of values that can be derived.  Celestial Tools is configured to give the set with the value of Asm LHA closer to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the actual value of LHA." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For the NASR method, after the ""NASR"" button is activated the user can select whether to use the Auxiliary Table found in the pre-1999/post-2004 " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Nautical Almanacs or that found in the 1999-2004 Nautical Almanacs.  The default is the pre-1999/post-2004 set.  Whenever this option is changed, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the calculation is done without having to activate the ""NASR"" button." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "A little explanation is in order.  In the late 1990s, USPS produced its own version of the Auxiliary Table, called the ""ALTITUDE CORRECTION TABLE for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The Nautical Almanac Sight Reduction Table"".  Its purpose was twofold.  It had a revised format which made it easier to determine the signs of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "corrections, and it ""corrected"" the tabulated values of corr1 and corr2 to match what would be derived from using a calculator and applying standard " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rounding techniques. (The single row that did not conform to this design in the Auxiliary Table was the values for P 30° and Z2 60°.  The Auxiliary Table " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "values for corr1 are one less than the USPS version values when P° is 30 and F' is odd.  The Auxiliary Table values for corr2 are one less than the USPS " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "version values when Z2° is 60 and A' is odd.)  This table was well-received, and replaced the original Auxiliary Table starting with the 1999 Nautical " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Almanac. However, starting in 2005, the Nautical Almanac maintained the improved format of the USPS version, but went back to the ""uncorrected"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "values of corr1 and corr2." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The NASR method program is capable of producing results outside the range of the tables, generally for objects that have a negative altitude, i.e. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "below the horizon.  This is not of significant interest to mariners." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For the Law of Cosines, the Estimated Position (EP) is the point at the end of the intercept line through which goes the line of position.  For all methods " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "that use an AP rather than a DR, this point is not the Estimated Position as normally defined, since the intercept starts at an Assumed Position (AP) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "instead of at a DR position or a Known Position (KP), and is called AP/EP in Celestial Tools to distinguish it from a normal EP.  (It is only valid from a fixed " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "position, not from a moving vessel.  One of the rhumb line methods of The Sailings can be used to advance an AP/EP.)  In either case, this point should " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "be useful in checking the accuracy of a plot.  For NASR, the DR-LOP distance is also shown, which, if the DR position is a known position (KP), is a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "measurment of the quality of the sight.  From this, the real EP,  the point on the LOP closest to the DR position, is calculated and displayed.  These " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "results will not necessarily match those obtained by the Law of Cosines because of the difference in precision and rounding and the skewing of the LOP " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "if there is sufficient difference in the azimuths derived by the two methods." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For Pub. 249, the program should operate properly even outside the declination range of 29°N to 29°S of the tables." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For Pub. 229, the DSD value and correction are generally only needed for values of Hc greater than 60° and certain conditions of latitude, declination, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and LHA.  After the ""Pub. 229"" button is activated, an ""Always use DSD"" checkbox will appear in the data display area, next to ""Pub 229"".   If this box is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "unchecked (the default), the DSD value and correction will only be included if the DSD correction exceeds 0.25'.  This should correspond to the tabular " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "values of d printed in italic type followed by a small dot.  If it is checked, the DSD value and correction will be included whether it is needed or not.  If " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the DSD value and correction are needed, the checkbox will be disabled.  (Checking or unchecking this box has the same effect as activating the ""Pub. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "229"" button:  the output display area is updated.) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For H.O. 211, after the ""H.O. 211"" button is activated the user can select whether to use Original (Ageton) or Compact (Ageton-Bayless) tables.  The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "default is the Compact tables.  (The original tables included entries for half-minutes of arc, which were deleted from the compact tables.) (Note that " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "changing this option has the same effect as activating the ""H.O. 211"" button:  the output display area is updated.)  For the Original tables, meridian " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "angle t and declination must be at least 0.3'.  For the  Compact tables, meridian angle t and declination must be at least 0.5'.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "H.O. 211 has a ""forbidden zone"", generally considered to be where K is between 82° and 98° (though some sources have smaller ranges), where an " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "intercept error of up to 30 miles may result (less if interpolation of the tables is used).  The USPS recommendation is to discard the sight.  However, if K " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is between 82° and 98°, Celestial Tools will interpolate (actually calculate) for the second B value.  When this occurs, either with the Compact or Original " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Tables, a message will appear indicating this, and giving the option of using the Sadler Technique, a modified form of H.O. 211 for use in the ""forbidden " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "zone"", which gives more accurate results.  For the Sadler Technique with the Original tables, meridian angle t must be at least 0.3' away from 90°.  With " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the  Compact tables, meridian angle t must be at least 0.5' away from 90°." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For H.O. 214, after the ""H.O. 214"" button is activated the user can select one of three possible solutions:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "1) Solution for line of position, using delta d correction.  This is the primary method for which the tables were originally designed, and is the default.  The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "solution is short and simple, essentially being plotted from an assumed (AP) latitude and longitude.  (The AP/EP is referenced to Asm L and Asm Lo.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "2) Solution for line of position, using both delta d and delta t corrections.  This is used if it is desired to plot from an AP latitude and a DR longitude.  (The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "AP/EP is referenced to Asm L and DR Lo.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "3) Solution for position line from the DR position using delta d, delta t, and delta L.  (No AP/EP or DR-LOP distance will be shown.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Note that changing this option has the same effect as activating the ""H.O. 214"" button:  the output display area is updated.)  H.A. is the equivalent of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "meridian angle t.  The use of delta t is not in general recommended when the altitude of the observed body is greater than 80°, but it will be included in " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the solution nevertheless.  The azimuth obtained from the tables is correct for the values with which the tables were entered, and for plotting lines of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "position generally need no correction.  If more accuracy is desired, the azimuth may be interpolated, but this will not be done by Celestial Tools." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For H.O. 208, the assumed LHA (the LHA to the nearest whole degree) cannot be 0° or 180°.  When high altitudes are observed near mereidian transit, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "selecting an assumed position to fit the tables may produce an appreciable error in azimuth.  Under these circumstances, interpolation to minutes of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "latitude is recommended, but will not be done by Celestial Tools.  Note that for H.O. 208, for a latitude of zero, the name of the latitude in the data " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "entry section is automatically changed to the name of the declination regardless of how it was originally set." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Two versions of the S-Table are provided:  the original (the default), by Mike Pepperday, which was included in the Nautical Almanac for a few years in " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the early '90s, and is still available as a booklet; and a modified version, by Rodger E. Farley, available in his book ""Celestial Navigation in a Teacup"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(formerly ""The Armchair Celestial Navigator"").  Both versions are derivatives of H.O. 211, and, as such, also have a ""forbidden zone""  where K is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "between 82° and 98°, which is handled in the same manner as in H.O. 211 .  The worksheeet for the Pepperday version as shown in the Nautical " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Almanac and the booklet is very similar to the H.O. 211 worksheet.  (Pepperday revised it to an improved version after the publication of the booklet, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "but it was never published.)  The Farley version uses an original worksheet.  In both cases Celestial Tools uses a worksheet similar to that of H.O. 211, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "but with the nomenclature changed to agree with the particular version being used." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The Farley version uses + for N and W, and - for S and E.  It also uses an unconventional definition of LHA, similar to meridian angle t.  For example, if " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "LHA is 350°, it will be shown as -10°.  The Farley version also does not mention the interpolation requirement where the value of the derived parameter " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "K is near 90° (as in H.O. 211), but there is an implication in the example in the book that ""eyeball interpolation"" should always be done for any " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "parameter.  (The Pepperday version specifically says not to bother using anything but the nearest tabulated value except in the case of K near 90°.)  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Celestial Tools, however, is programmed so that interpolation is only done when the K value is from 82° to 98°." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For the Weems Line of Position Book, after the ""Weems LPB"" button is activated, an ""Interpolate Table B"" checkbox will appear in upper left corner of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the data display area.   If this box is unchecked (the default), the value of K~d is rounded to the nearest whole minute before calculating the value of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "B, and Hc is rounded to whole minutes, as was done in examples in the second (and, it is believed, the first) edition of the book.  If it is checked, the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "value of K~d to tenths of a minute is used for calculating the value of B, and Hc is rounded to tenths of minutes, as was done in examples in the third " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(and, it is believed, the fourth) edition of the book.  This checkbox is only associated with the calculation of Hc, to the left of the vertical dotted line.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Checking or unchecking this box has the same effect as activating the ""Weems LPB"" button:  the output display area is updated.)  All editions of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Weems Line of Position Book used Rust's Azimuth Diagram to determine Z and Zn.  The third and fourth editions added a tabular method for that " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "purpose.  Celestial Tools displays Z and Zn, calculated from the formula from which the Rust diagram was constructed, to the left of the vertical dotted " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "line on the display.  The tabular method is shown to the right of the vertical dotted line.  Interpolation of Table B is never used:  the table is entered with " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "angles rounded to whole minutes, and B values are extracted rounded to units.  (Note that in cases where it might not be clear, the table used (A or B) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is embedded in the arrow symbols, and whether the table is entered from the top or bottom is indicated.)  It should be noted that this method uses an " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "unconventional definition of azimuth angle (Z).  The prefix is determined by whether the body is north or south of the observer, and the maximum value " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is 90°, where in most methods the prefix is the elevated pole, and the maximum value is 180°.  (In all methods the suffix is determined by whether the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "body is east or west of the observer.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Although examples in some books indicate that this is not required, in all sight reduction methods that use an assumed longitude to calculate a whole " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "degree value of LHA, Celestial Tools will always select an assumed longitude that is within 30' of the DR longitude.  This will result in a whole-degree " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "value of assumed LHA that is closest to the actual LHA." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "In all sight reduction methods that plot from an assumed longitude, if the DR longitude is close to 0° or 180°, the assumed longitude might not be in the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "same hemisphere as the DR longitude.  In those cases, the standard form ofassumed longitude will be displayed, with the appropriate operation.  For " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "example, If the DR longitude is 0°20'W and the GHA is 0°50', Celestial Tools will display the assumed longitude as (-)  0°10'E rather than (+) 359°50'W." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "When switching from one sight reduction method to another, or after pressing ""Clear All"" or ""Clear except DR"", any options will be left in the state they " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "were last in." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Reductions by the Law of Cosines method can be saved (there is no provision for doing this with any of the other methods), using the ""Save for Fix"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "button, and the last twelve saved are retained.  After a minimum of two sights are reduced by the Law of Cosines method and saved, you have the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "option of establishing a fix, with the ""Establish Fix"" button, using sights selected from the list of up to twelve. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If taking sights from a moving vessel, the  times of the sights must be entered, only accurate enough to establish the chronological order of the sights.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Sights with times and without times cannot be mixed.)  The time of the fix is the time of the latest sight selected.  (At sea, if the time between the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "earliest and latest sights is more than 20 minutes, the fix should be considered a Running Fix.)  Do not use times that cross midnight.  Adjust times to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "avoid this; the times only need to correctly represent chronological order.  If sights are taken from a fixed position, e.g. from a Known Position (KP) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "when taking sights for a sight folder, the times are not required, but all sights selected for the fix must have the same DR position.  Keep in mind that" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "you should expect a small difference between the calculated fix and a plotted fix if the plotted fix was established with a sight reduction method that " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "plots from an Assumed Position (AP) (e.g. the Nautical Almanac Sight Reduction method) rather than one that plots from a DR position (Law of Cosines " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "in Celestial Tools).  (Although Celestial Tools has no provision to establish a fix from sights taken by any method other than the Law of Cosines, reducing " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "these sights with the Law of Cosines should result in a fix that is relatively close to what would be established using other reduction methods.  Fixes " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "established from methods that plot from an assumed position, even if from a moving vessel, should be within one nautical mile or so from the fix " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "established by the Law of Cosines.)  In addition to the latitude and longitude of the fix, the distance and bearing from the DR to the fix will be displayed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "To include a Noon Sight as part of the list of sights saved for a fix, use the Ho, Dec, and L from the Noon Sight.  Set LHA equal to zero by setting GHA " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "equal to LoW or 360-LoE.  Reduce the sight with the ""Law of Cosines"" button, then save it with the ""Save for Fix"" button." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Caution:  Versions of Celestial Tools prior to V2.3.0 had a bug that prevented some valid sets of sights from establishing a fix.  This bug was removed, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "with the consequence that almost any set of sights will produce a fix, regardless of cut or length of intercept.  It is left to the user to select appropriate " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sights." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "After each reduction is done a ""Meridian Diagram"" button becomes available.  Pressing this button opens another window showing the Projection on the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Plane of the Celestial Meridian, based on the values in the reduction.  There is the option of representing the hour circles and vertical circles as accurate " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "ellipses (default) or as less accurate arcs of circles.  Vertical circles and hour circles are solid of the body is to the west, dashed if to the east.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Construction lines for both the hour circle and vertical circle are shown.  The position of the body is represented by a dot, which is located at the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "intersection of the parallel of altitude and the parallel of declination, regardless of the hour circle or vertical circle.  If circles are used, the hour circle and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "vertical circle are forced to pass through the body, and the plotted values of LHA and Zn may not agree with the calculated values.  With good input " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "data, the differences are not expected to exceed 4 degrees.  When ellipses are used, if the input data is good, the hour circle and vertical circle should " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "intersect at (or at least near) the intersection of the parallel of altitude and parallel of declination.  If not, look for an error in the data input, which " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "would probably also have caused an excessively large intercept value.  Since when circles are used the hour circle and vertical circle are forced to pass " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "through the intersection of the parallel of altitude and parallel of declination, the quality of the input data cannot be judged.  The graphics associated " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "with each parameter are color-coded; the color legend appears in the upper left corner of the window.  This tool is shared with the Sight Reduction & " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Fix tool, and will use the data from the last reduction done with either of the two.  The ""Meridian Diagram"" button is enabled only once for each " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "reduction.  To enable it again, the ""Law of Cosines"" or the ""NASR"" button must be pressed.  However, if the Meridian Diagram windows is already " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "opened, switching between ""Ellipses"" and ""Circles"" will create a meridian diagram based on the last reduction done.  To use new values, one of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "seven sight reduction method buttons must be pressed again." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Pressing the ""Clear All"" button clears all inputs and outputs.  Pressing the ""Clear except DR"" button leaves the DR L and DR Lo as they were." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  These tools should reproduce the values in the corresponding parts of the USPS SR96 form exactly, with the possible exception " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "for NASR noted above, and for Pub. 249 and Pub. 229 noted below.  In the Law of Cosines, all values of latitude, LHA, and declination are rounded to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "five decimal places, to conform to the method used in the examples in the JN and N student manuals, and these values are used in subsequent " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculations.  The calculated value of Hc is rounded to five decimal places, and this value is used in subsequent calculations.  However, depending on " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "how the student does the calculations, e.g. using unrounded values stored in memory, and even the model of the calculator used, the value of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "decimal representation of Hc may differ in the fifth, and possibly fourth, decimal place, and the degrees and minutes representation may differ by 0.1', " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "from the student's values.  A difference of 0.1° in the value of Z is also possible.  In the methods that use an AP, the DR-LOP distance is rounded to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "tenths of a nautical mile.  The  EP L and EP Lo should agree with a careful plot within 0.1' for LoC and 0.3' for the other methods.  A two-body fix (for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Law of Cosines only) should agree fairly well with a plot, generally within 0.2' of latitude and longitude, but a three (or more)-body fix may not agree " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "that well with a plot because of the uncertainty in determining the fix position of the plot.  When comparing a fix plot based on a methods that use an " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "AP with the LoC calculated fix, differences of up to about 1' of latitude and longitude can be expected.  The distance and bearing from the DR to the fix " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "are rounded to tenths of a nautical mile and whole degrees, respectively." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For all methods, the final value of Zn is rounded to whole degrees, the current USPS standard, which may be contrary to some of the old SR forms, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "which rounded Zn to tenths of a degree.  For the form of the Law of Cosine used, the azimuth of bodies near the zenith will not be accurate." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For Pub. 249, the values of Tab Hc and Tab d may differ from the tables by 1'." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For Pub. 229, all correction interpolations are done mathematically, and will occasionally be at a variance with the interpolation table.  This variance " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "should not exceed 0.1', and is most likely to occur for the value of d2 corr." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "H.O. 211 notes:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "1) Both the compact and original versions have most of the tabular data rounded to the nearest whole number.  However, the compact version show " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "values below 166 to once decimal place, and the original version shows values below 239 to one decimal place.  The example in the compact version " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "shows one of these low values rounded to a whole number, but an example in the original version uses the tenths.  However, Celestial Tools will abide " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "by the USPS rules for the compact version:  ""Record all decimal values exactly as shown in the Compact Table.  Do not round to the next whole number. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Carry all decimal values forward and use for all computations.""" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "2) If ""Compact"" is selected, input latitude and declination and the calculated value of K~L will be shown rounded to the nearest minute.  If ""Original"" is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "selected, input latitude and declination and the calculated value of K~L will be shown rounded to the nearest half minute.  These are the values actually " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "used to enter the table, which are of more help to the student than the real values.  If latitude and declination do not exactly correspond to a tabulated " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "value, improved accuracy can be obtained with interpolation, but this is generally not done, and is not done by Celestial Tools." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "3) From the ""Compact Signt Reduction Table"" booklet, first edition:  ""Accuracy decreases as K approaches 90° and an error of several miles may result.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Consequently, it is good practice to discard any sight in which K is between 82° and 98°.  Interpolation of the table will improve the result somewhat if " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the salvation of the sight is imperative.""  Celestial Tools does not interpolate in these cases, but provides the option of using the Sadler Technique, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "described in the second edition, in these cases." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "4) When the body is near or on the prime vertical, the last A value (used to determine Z) may be negative.  If so, it will be set to zero and Z will be 90°." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "5) Due to the vagaries of rounding, there will occasionally be a difference of one unit in the least significant figure of the calculated tabular values" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "compared to the actual tabular values." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For H.O. 214, there will occasionally be a difference of 1 unit (0.01) in the value of delta t compared to the tabular values.  All corrections are not " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculated mathematically, but are done by emulating the multiplication tables at the end of the H.O. 214 book, and should match the tables well.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The tables, however, could be off by no more than 0.1' compared to a mathemical calculation." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For H.O. 208, there will occasionally be a difference of 1 unit in the values of A, B, C, and D, compared to the tabular values, and other differences " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "resulting as a consequence of these - no more than 0.2' in intercept and no error in azimuth." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For both versions of the S-Table, the tabular values produced by Celestial Tools should be within 0.001 of the printed values.  When deriving an angle " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "from a tabulated value, if there is a group of the same tabulated value, Celestial Tools will try to use the average value.  Due to the vagaries of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rounding, this can result in an angle that differs from the printed values by 1'.  Also, the Farley version example in the book shows a couple of angles to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "tenths of a minute.  Celestial Tools will round these values to whole minutes." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For the Weems Line of Position Book, the A and B values calculated by Celestial Tools may disagree with the tabular or interpolated B values by one " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "least significant digit, i.e. if the tabular values are to units, the disagreement might be 1; if the tabular values are to tenths, the disagreement might be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "0.1.  (In the case of interpolated values, the program calculates the values using linear interpolation, the way it would be done manually, which does " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "not necessarily agree with values which would be determined by direct calculation.)  Though examples in the third edition of the book show values of A " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "always rounded to units, Celestial Tools will show them to the resolution displayed in the table, and complete the calculation using this resolution.  The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "angles calculated by Celestial Tools may disagree with the tabular or interpolated values by 0.1'.  The values of Z and Zn calculated by formula may " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "disagree with examples in the book by 0.1° if the examples are shown to that resolution." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
