			"GENERAL" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  Although the data produced by Celestial Tools is fairly accurate, the program should not be used for navigation.  Its primary purpose is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "instructional:  to aid students in planning sights; to allow students to quickly check the quality of sights; and to help students find errors in their work.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "It is not intended to do the work for the student." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b.  System requirements" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	i. Operating System:  Windows 95 or later" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	ii. CPU:  Anything as old as a 486-33 should provide reasonable performance" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	iii. Support files:  The Visual Basic 6 runtime files must be on your computer.  These files comes with Windows Me, Windows 2000 	" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	Professional, Windows XP, Windows Vista, Windows 7, Windows 8, and Windows 10, or may have been installed during the installation of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	another program.  If they are not present, your computer will let you know when you try to run the program.  The latest version can be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	downloaded from www.microsoft.com as a self-extracting executable, currently VBRUN60SP6.EXE, about a 1MB download.  (If you have " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	gotten this far, you already have them.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	iv. Hard disk space:  3148KB for CelestialTools540.exe.  An additional 1.5MB or so if the Visual Basic runtime files are needed.  Size of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	Favorite_Places.txt is negligible (106 bytes per location; a 4KB cluster could handle 38 locations)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	v. Memory:  Less than 10MB available memory if all tools are running." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	vi. Screen resolution:  800x600 or greater.  If you are using 800x600 and your Windows taskbar is at the bottom of the screen and Auto hide " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	is not enabled, the bottom of the Sight Reduction window will be obscured by the taskbar.  It is recommended that Auto hide be enabled or 	" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	the taskbar be moved to the right side of the screen.  The same recommendation is made for any other toolbars, such as the Microsoft Office " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	toolbar, that might obscure part of a window." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	vii. Fonts:  Tahoma, Arial, Courier New, and Symbol, provided with Windows.  (Windows 95 will substitute MS Sans Serif for Tahoma.)  With " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	the exception of Windows 10, font size must be set to 96 dpi (called small, smaller, standard, normal, or 100% depending on operating " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	system)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	viii. Mouse:  Recommended, but rarely required" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "	ix. Printer:  Recommended" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Windows: Most of the working windows have two types of sections:  data entry and output display.  All windows can be minimized and moved but " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "cannot be maximized or resized." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "d. Tool Tip Text: When the cursor is over many of the items in the data entry section of a window, a tool tip will appear, showing information such as " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the allowable input range." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "e. Inputs:  The inputs for all modules are set up to require minimum keystrokes. For example, a longitude of ""072"" degrees and ""04.0"" minutes can " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "simply be entered as ""72"" and ""4"".  There is considerable error checking, warning you if you have entered obviously incorrect values.  In certain cases, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "if you have entered an illegal value, the program will not let you move on until you enter a legal value.  Except for the Interpolation tool, which has " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "special rules; the Observed ZT of LAN in Noon Sight; the desired ZT for body visibility in Sight Planner, which cannot be left blank; and the DR L in Sight " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Reduction Latitude by altitude of Polaris, which has special meaning when left blank, numerical inputs initially left blank are treated as zero, but " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "subsequent zero entries should be of the proper format as shown in the associated tool tip text.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Most arc-minute data input boxes expect a format of MM.m, i.e. four characters including the decimal point, with only one digit after the decimal point.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Currently there is nothing in Celestial Tools to prevent inputs of M.mm or .mmm.  Be careful with these boxes.  Also, if one of these boxes has a value in " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "it that includes a decimal point, and you wish to change it to a value that starts with a decimal point, it is best not to highlight the original value and try " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to enter the new value.  It will not accept an initial decimal point in these circumstances.  It is best to to delete the original value before entering the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "new value, or start the new value with a zero, followed by the decimal point." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note:  Celestial Tools only accepts digits and dots (periods) for numerical inputs.  It will work for computers set for a language other than U.S. English, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "but inputs must use dots (periods), rather than commas (or anything else), as decimal separators, regardless of the language.  Outputs will be displayed " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "in the format of the selected language." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "f. ""Almanac"" Accuracy:  The Sight Planner, Sight Reduction, and Noon Sight tools contain a medium-precision ""almanac"" for the 57 navigational stars, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the four navigational planets, the Sun, the Moon, and Polaris, plus 70 additional ""helper"" stars (see Sight Planner Help), limited to the years 1901-2099.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "It also includes ""tables"" for dip, refraction, and Increments and Corrections. Accuracy details are described below, and values generally will not exactly " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "agree with the Nautical Almanac.  However, they are more than accurate enough to achieve results consistent with the purpose of the program." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "It should be noted that the Nautical Almanac itself does not claim perfect accuracy.  From page 261, paragraph 24, regarding the accuracy of the main " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "data:  ""The quantities tabulated in this Almanac are generally correct to the nearest 0.1'; the exception is the Sun's GHA which is deliberately adjusted " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "by up to 0.15' to reduce the error due to ignoring the v-correction....The largest error that can occur in the GHA or Dec of any body other than the Sun " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "or Moon is less than 0.2'; it may reach 0.25' for the GHA of the Sun and 0.3' for that of the Moon....In practice it may be expected that only one third " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of the values of GHA and Dec taken out will have errors larger than 0.05' and less than one tenth will have errors larger than 0.1'.""" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Positional accuracy of the bodies:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Considering the accuracy statements in the Nautical Almanac, for the Sight Reduction and Noon Sight tools the expected worst case errors for the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "parameters used to calculate the GHA and declination, compared to values extracted from the Nautical almanac, are:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Stars:  SHA 0.1' (Note 1); Dec 0.1' (Note 1); GHA Aries hr 0.1'; GHA Aries m s 0.0'; Dec 0.1'" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Planets:  GHA hr 0.1'; GHA m s 0.0'; v 0.1'; v corr 0.1' (Note 2); Dec hr 0.1'; d 0.1'; d corr 0.1' (Note 2); also see Note 3" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Sun:  GHA hr 0.1' (Note 4); GHA m s 0.0; Dec hr 0.1'; d 0.1'; d corr 0.1' (Note 2)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Moon:  GHA hr 0.1'; GHA m s 0.0; v 0.1'; v corr 0.1' (Note 2); Dec hr 0.1'; d 0.1'; d corr 0.1' (Note 2)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note 1:  For the SHA and declination of the stars, the Nautical Almanac uses the value for UT 12h of the middle day of the three days covered by a daily " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "page.  Celestial Tools has options to do it that way or using the actual date and time of the sight for its calculation of SHA.  In either case a discrepancy " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of no more than 0.1' is expected. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note 2:  The v corr and d corr should be accurate for whatever v or d value is calculated, but since the calculated v or d value can have an error of 0.1', " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "so can v corr and d corr.  The v and d values of the planets and the d value of the Sun listed in the Nautical Almanac are ""averages"" for the three days " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "shown on the page.    For the Sun and planets, the Sight Reduction tool has two modes.  In the Nautical Almanac mode Celestial Tools calculates the d " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "value for the Sun and the v and d values for the planets using an ""average"" for the three days shown on the page.  In the Accurate mode it calculates " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "these values for the date and time of the sight.  In the Noon Sight tool, only the ""average"" value is used to calculate d.  Celestial Tools calculates the v " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "corr and d corr based on the Greenwich year of the sight.  See Yellow Pages (I&C) Help regarding differences in Nautical Almanac Increments and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Corrections tables." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note 3:  The planet Venus exhibits phases like the Moon, which can be seen with optical aid.  From 1952 to 1984 the additional corrections for Venus " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "listed in the Nautical Almanac allowed for both parallax and phase.  The phase correction was required because the tabulated position was for the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "planet's center of disk.  Before 1952 and since 1985 the tabulated position of Venus is for its center of light, and the phase correction is incorporated " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "into the tabulated values of GHA and Dec.  Celestial Tools does not correct for phase, i.e. it calculates the position of the center of disk (as do most " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sources other than the Nautical Almanac), so the GHA of Venus can be as much as an additional 0.5' off compared to the Nautical Almanac for years " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "other than 1952-1984.  (Mars also exhibits phases, but the effect is negligible.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note 4:  0.1' for Sight Reduction when set for ""NA val. of hourly GHA/d"" and for Noon Sight.  (0.0' for about 99% of the cases.)  0.2' for Sight " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Reduction when set for ""Accurate val. of hourly GHA/d"" and for Sight Planner Star Finder Data." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(The ""averages"" used by the Nautical Almanac to determine the v and d values for the planets and the d value for the Sun are based on the difference " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "between the associated value at 0h UT of the middle day of the page and 0h UT on the following day, divided by 24, as confirmed by Catherine " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Hohenkerk of HMNAO.  This is in contrast to what is said in Bowditch (through the 2002 edition), which states that they are based on the difference " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "between the 1200 UT value and the 1300 UT value of the middle day.  According to Sean Urban, Chief of the Nautical Almanac Office of the US Naval " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Observatory, these correction will be made in the next edition of Bowditch, expected mid-2017.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The Sight Reduction tool attempts to duplicate the steps of a manual reduction, adding several parameters, each with a potential error, to get a total.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "As such, the resulting GHA or declination might not match the values obtained from a source that calculates GHA and declination directly, such as the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Sight Planner Star Finder Data tool.  Considering this, the expected worst case errors for GHA and declination are:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Stars:  GHA 0.2'; Dec 0.1'" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Planets:  GHA 0.2' (0.7' for Venus compared to Nautical Almanacs before 1952 and since 1985); Dec 0.2'" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Sun:  GHA 0.2' (when set for ""NA val. of hourly GHA""); Dec 0.2'" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Moon:  GHA 0.2'; Dec 0.2'" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For Latitude by Altitude of Polaris, the values of a0, a1, and a2 are expected to agree with those extracted from the Nautical Almanac within 0.1'.  It is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "unlikely, however, that all three will be off at the same time.  Often, if one value is 0.1' too high another will be 0.1' too low, resulting in the proper total " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "correction  The calculated Zn should agree with the Nautical Almanac within 0.1°." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The Sight Planner tool calculates all values directly, but rounds azimuths and altitudes to whole degrees before creating the list of visible bodies.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Therefore it is possible for there to be a one degree error in the values listed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Altitude corrections:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The calculated value of dip will agree with the Nautical Almanac dip tables for values of height of eye up to 70.5 feet and 21.4 meters.  For greater " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "heights of eye, generally not a concern of the student, there are occasional discrepancies of 0.1'.  In the ranges of heights of eye of 8-10 feet and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "2.4-3 meters, which are covered by both the interpolation and critical portions of the dip table, the calculated value of dip will agree with the critical " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "table.  (Note, for example, that the interpolated and critical portions of the dip table disagree at 8.1, 8.2, 8.7, and 9.8 feet.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Computed refraction (the Main altitude correction for the stars and planets, but affecting all bodies) will agree with the Nautical Almanac for apparent " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "altitudes greater than about 10°  (in Sight Reduction, when Show Ho corrections as SR Form is selected) , and may be a few tenths of a minute off for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "lower altitudes.  For non-standard temperature and pressure, the additional refraction correction may be as much as several minutes off the Nautical " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Almanac value for very low altitudes.  (When Show Ho corrections as Parameters is selected in Sight Reduction, there may be a larger difference for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "refraction.)  The refraction corrections used by the Nautical Almanac changed in 2004.  For apparent altitudes less than about 10°, Celestial Tools uses " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the formula from the Sight Reduction Procedures section of the Nautical Almanac (which did not change until 2005), based on the Greenwich year " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "derived from the date entered in the data entry section of the form in use (Sight Reduction & Fix or Noon Sight).  (This is only a significant factor for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "altitudes less than 2°.  However, this change also affected the critical values of apparent altitude on the Altitude Corrections Table " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "10°-90°-Sun,Stars,Planets (Table A2), so care should be taken to use the correct table when doing a manual calculation.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The additional correction for the planets Venus and Mars (parallax) should agree with 1985 and later Nautical Almanacs within 0.1.  Almanacs from 1952 " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to 1984 included a phase correction for Venus in addition to parallax.  Since 1985 the phase correction has been incorporated in the tabulations for the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "GHA and Dec.   Celestial Tools only considers parallax, so for Almanac years prior to 1985 a discrepancy of a few tenths of an arc-minute can be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "expected in the additional correction for Venus. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For dip short, Celestial Tools uses the formula in recent (1981 or later) editions of Bowditch.  This formula is exact for the refraction model adopted.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Current JN and N course materials (and the back of the SR form) use an approximate formula found in earlier editions of Bowditch, which matches the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "exact formula in most cases, but differences, never exceeding 0.3', do appear for very short distances, and there is an occasional difference of 0.1' " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "elsewhere.  Because the approximate formula can develop unacceptably large errors with large heights of eye coupled with short distances, it should " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "not be used if it results in a dip that exceeds 200' (3º20').  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Regarding the altitude correction for the Sun, for a given limb and apparent altitude, the Almanac Altitude Correction Tables use an average value of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "semi-diameter over each of the six-month periods tabulated (and, on the bottom of the Sun column on each daily page, an average value of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "semi-diameter for the three days covered by the page).  This allows a year's worth of corrections to occupy only a third of a page, with a maximum " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "error of only a few tenths of an arc minute.  In Sight Reduction and Noon Sight, if Show Ho corrections as SR Form is selected, Celestial Tools will " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "similarly use an average value of semi-diameter.  If Show Ho corrections as Parameters is selected, Celestial Tools uses the actual date and time in its " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "computation.  Additionally, from 1954 through 1969, the Almanac included an irradiation correction of -1.2' for the upper limb of the Sun, which is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "included in Celestial Tools.  The refraction correction change of 2004 also affected the transition points of this table.  In all cases, the output of Celestial " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Tools may not agree with that extracted from the Almanac.  If Show Ho corrections as SR form is selected, expected worst case error is 0.1' compared " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to the Sun Altitude Correction Table or the semi-diameter value at the bottom of the Sun column of the daily page.   If Show Ho corrections as " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Parameters is selected, the values, though more accurate, may be in less agreement with the Almanac.  Whichever mode is selected, the corresponding " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "value of Ho is used in the Law of Cosines calculation." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The horizontal parallax (HP) of the Moon is expected to be within 0.1' of the value extracted from the Nautical Almanac, and is based on the whole UT " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "hour nearest to the time of observation, which could be the hour following the observation.  (This is the method on page 280 of the Nautical Almanac, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and in the USPS Navigation Student Manual since N2009.)  The Main and Add'l corrections for the Moon are expected to agree with the Nautical Almanac " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "within 0.1 (using the refraction formula for the entered year)." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Remember, though, that the purpose of Celestial Tools is not to do the student's work, but to provide an aid in locating errors." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "g. Data display ""anomalies"":  Versions of Celestial Tools prior to V4.0.0 used lower precision algorithms, so, in order to avoid additional errors, for most " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "tools, arithmetic was done to the full precision of the computer, followed by rounding.  (An exception to this rule was Height of Eye, where inches and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "centimeters were converted to feet and meters, respectively, which were then rounded to one decimal place for dip calculation and display purposes.)  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Occasionally this resulted in the whole not being equal to the sum of the parts.  Take, for example, 1.06 + 1.06.  If rounding to one decimal place is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "done first, the result would be 1.1 + 1.1 = 2.2. If rounding to one decimal place is done last, you would have 1.06 + 1.06 = 2.12, resulting in a display " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of 1.1 + 1.1 = 2.1.  With the improved accuracy of V4.0.0, it was no longer felt that this was necessary.  Rounding is always done first, so the whole " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "will equal the sum of the parts.  When calculating estimated positions or fixes, the values of intercept and azimuth are rounded to tenths of a nautical " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "mile and whole degrees, respectively, before the calculations are made, to more closely match a manual plot." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "In versions of Celestial Tool prior to V4.0.0, it might also have been noticed that an angle calculated by the program (one not entered by the user) in " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "degrees and minutes might not equal its representation in decimal degrees.  This was because the calculation was done in decimal degrees to the full " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "precision of the computer, then converted to degrees and minutes, followed by rounding the minutes to one decimal place.  Again, with the improved " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "accuracy of V4.0.0, the representation in decimal degrees will be correct for the angle displayed in degrees and minutes." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "One ""anomaly"" that has been retained in V4.0.0 and later is that, in most cases, the program does not round a number for one displayed value then " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "round it again for a subsequent displayed value.  This can result in an ""anomaly"".  As an example, say Sight Reduction calculates a value for Z of N " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "49.51... W.  Rounded to one decimal place, this is displayed as N 49.5 W.  When this is converted to Zn, the unrounded value of Z is rounded to whole " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "degrees, displaying a Zn value of 310.  If the rounded value of Z were used, a Zn value of 311 would be displayed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For the SR Methods tool, this ""anomaly"" will not occur.  In order to match manual sight reductions, intermediate values are rounded to the required " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "precision then used in subsequent calculations.  A Z of N 49.5 W results in a Zn of 311." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "h. Rounding:  Celestial Tools rounds by the method currently taught by the United States Power Squadrons, ""rounding upward"".  For instance, if " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rounding to a whole number, 34.0-34.4 round to 34, and 34.5-34.9 round to 35.  In the past ""rounding to the even"", also known as ""banker's rounding"", " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a method still used in some references, was used.  When using this method to round to a whole number, .5 is dropped if preceded by an even number, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "but raising to the next whole number if preceded by an odd number.  For instance, 34.5 would round to 34, but 35.5 would round to 36. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "i. Printing:  All of the windows worth printing have a small button with an icon of a printer in the upper right-hand corner below the Close button.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Except for the case of the Help window, when this button is activated, a bitmapped image of the window, including the title bar and border, is sent to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the selected printer.  For the Help window, the text alone is printed for all 20 topics (tabs) or any individual topic.  Individual words, sentences, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "paragraphs, etc. can be cut and pasted into a text editor or word processor (e.g. Windows Notepad) and printed from there.  With the exception of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Help, where this does not apply, all portions of a window intended to be printed must be contained within the monitor screen; offscreen portions will not " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "be printed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Printer selection is done from the main menu.  When the ""Select Printer"" button is activated, a window with a drop-down list of available printers " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "appears.  The default is the Windows default printer, but any of the others can be selected.  The selected printer is active for all the tools of Celestial " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Tools, but does not affect any other program." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "j. Dates and times:  The default date is the system date.  It can be changed to any date from 1901 to 2099.  Invalid dates will produce an error " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "message." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "A note about Manual Zone Descriptions:  Although there are a limited number of locations that do not use whole hours as their zone description, there is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "an even more limited number of hour values that are associated with the two possible minute values, 30 and 45.  Nevertheless, Celestial Tools allows for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "any hour value to be associated with those minute values.  Negative manual zone descriptions are entered by putting a minus sign as the first character " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of the ZD h box.  If a ZD of -0h30m or -0h45m is desired, a ""-"" or a ""-0"" should be entered in the ZD h box.  Positive manual zone descriptions will " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "accept, but do not requre, a ""+""." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "k. Contact information:  Please send any comments, suggestions, or recommendations to slk1000@aol.com." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
