			"SIGHT PLANNER" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  ""Twilight"" calculator and ""Star Finder"".  It will calculate the times of the Sun's rising and setting phenomena (twilights) and azimuths of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sunrise and sunset for the entered date and location, and find the azimuth, altitude, and magnitude of the navigational bodies which are above the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "horizon at a selected time, without the need to consult an almanac or tables or to use a Rude (2102-D) Star Finder.  (Since the program is intended to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "emulate the Rude Star Finder, it does not include corrections for refraction and dip.)  It will also calculate the availability data for a Sun-Moon fix for the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "entered date, location, azimuth range, and minimum altitude.  In addition, it will calculate the times (accurately or using the approximate method " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "currently taught in N) and azimuths of moonrise and moonset and the phase of the Moon for the entered date and location." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:  Initial required inputs are date and DR latitude and longitude.  Zone Description is automatically calculated based on longitude, but any " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "civil standard time zone can be entered manually to allow for time zones not based on longitude, or for Universal Time.  As a convenience feature, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the UT (GMT) option forces time outputs to be in Universal Time.  Check the DST box if the timepiece is set for Daylight Savings Time.  Select whether " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the azimuths of the Sun and Moon should be shown for when the upper limb or the center of the body is on the visible horizon (see below).  Moon rise " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and set data is calculated fairly accurately unless the ""Approximate Moon rise and set data"" box is checked, in which case the accuracy will be similar to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "that of the approximate method currently taught in the N course.  (Checking or unchecking that box has the same effect as activating the ""Get Twilight " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Times/Moon Data"" button.)  After activating the ""Get Twilight Times/Moon Data"" button, the program displays the zone times of sunrise, sunset, and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "civil, nautical, and astronomical morning and evening twilights in 24-hour format; the azimuths of sunrise and sunset (in parentheses, next to the times, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "if ""Upper Limb"" is selected); the times and azimuths of moonrise and moonset (if ""Upper Limb"" is selected), if they occur; and  the approximate phase of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the Moon at ZT 1200, expressed in percent illumination, and whether it is waxing or waning.  (Note that rises and sets are defined as when the upper " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "limb of the body is on the visible horizon.)  Any of the entered values can be changed at any time and the calculations redone." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""Center"" is selected, the Sun and Moon azimuths shows are for when the center of the body is on the visible horizon.  Comparing the compass bearing " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of a celestial body with a computer bearing provides an accurate means of checking the deviation of a compass at sea.  This is usually done by " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "measuring the body's amplitude, the angle between the body and the prime vertical (90° or 270°), measured along the horizon, when the center of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "body is on the visible horizon.  Amplitude is then applied to the appropriate prime vertical to get the true azimuth of the center of the body.  Celestial " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Tools calculates the true azimuth directly, and displays it to the nearest tenth of a degree, as would a manual calculation.  (Although these azimuths are " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "associated with the rises and sets, they actually occur shortly after the rises and shortly before the sets.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Note that changing between ""Upper Limb"" and ""Center"" has the same effect as activating the ""Get Twilight Times/Moon Data"" button:  the azimuths " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "are updated.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "A time of ""----"" indicates that the Sun phenomenon does not occur for the date and location entered (e.g. midsummer sun does not set in high latitudes). " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Note that when a manual time zone or DST is used, it is possible for solar phenomena to occur on the previous or next day.  For example, if the Start " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of AM Astronomical Twilight is 2336 and the Start of AM Nautical Twilight is 0058, the 2336 time is the previous day.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note that in higher latitudes (generally above 62°) the Moon can remain above or below the horizon all day.  A less well known quirk of the arctic is that " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "on certain days the Moon can rise or set twice.  (Try 23 June 1989, L 66°N, Lo 0°.) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Enter the zone time of interest for body visibility (i.e. above the horizon).  Any time can be entered (hhmm format), but in most cases it will be the start " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of AM civil twilight or the end of PM civil twilight, considered to be the middles of the optimum observing periods.  When the time is entered, a box next " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "to it will indicate whether the time entered occurs during daylight (yellow background), during twilight (blue background), or at night (black background).  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(For the purposes of this function, morning twilight is defined as the time of the start of AM nautical twilight through the minute before the time of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sunrise;  evening twilight is defined as the time of sunset through the minute before the time of the end of PM nautical twilight.)  This is intended to help " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "catch errors in entering the desired zone time - in most cases the box should be blue, indicating twilight.  If it is not, be sure the entered time is the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "desired time.  If a range of azimuths of interest for body visibility other than 0° to 360° (the default) is desired, select a single range of azimuths, going " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "clockwise.  (That is, from 10 to 350 would give a 340° range, but from 350 to 10 would give a 20° range.  Remember that sights on bodies that are not " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "above the available horizon could potentially be taken with a back sight.  To consider these, set the azimuth range from 0° to 360°.)  If desired, enter a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "minimum altitude for the Sun-Moon fix other than the default value of 15°, the minimum altitude for which temperature and barometric pressure " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "corrections are not required.  Acceptable values are whole degrees from 0 to 90. (If 0° is used, only the upper limbs will be above the horizon.)  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(Versions of Celestial Tools prior to V4.2.1 had an upper limit of 15°.  This change allows the times that the Sun and Moon are at a higher altitude to be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculated.)  Select either ""List Visible Bodies/Sun-Moon Fix"", ""View Visible Bodies"", or ""Star Finder Data""." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""List Visible Bodies/Sun-Moon Fix"" is selected, a table with three columns is displayed.  The three columns are for: the Sun, Moon, planets, and first " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "magnitude stars; second magnitude stars; and third magnitude stars.  They show the name, azimuth, altitude, and magnitude of bodies that are above " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the horizon. (Note that star magnitudes, as listed in the Nautical Almanac, changed in 2006.  The magnitudes shown in Sight Planner are based on the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Greenwich year derived from the date entered in the data entry section of the Sight Planner form.)  Within each column, the bodies within the azimuth " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "range specified are listed in order of increasing azimuth.  For the Moon, percent illumination is given instead of magnitude.  Bodies within the JN altitude " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "range of 15° to 75° are shown in bold type." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Also displayed is Sun-Moon fix availability data.  A box at the bottom of the third magnitude star column will indicate whether an acceptable Sun-Moon " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "fix is available for the entered date, location, azimuth range, and minimum altitude, and, if so, gives the range of zone times and the range of percent " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "illumination of the Moon.   An acceptable Sun-Moon fix is defined as having the centers (not the upper limbs) of the Sun and Moon above the entered " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "minimum altitude value, both bodies within the specified azimuth range, and the difference in azimuths between 45° and 135°.  Particular times, or even " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "entire dates, might be rejected by the user if it is felt that the Moon is too narrow.  Be aware that for certain dates and latitudes the maximum allowed " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "altitude of one of the bodies for a particular sight reduction method might be exceeded." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note that in all cases, including the variations of ""View Visible Bodies"" described below, if the time entered is that of sunrise, sunset, moonrise, or " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "moonset, the corresponding body will not be considered visible.  This is because the rise and set times are defined as when the upper limb of the body is" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "on the visible horizon, so the body is actually below the horizon.  A body is considered visible when its center is above the visible horizon, so, for " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "example, it might be several minutes after the time of sunrise before the Sun is visible." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""View Visible Bodies"" is selected, a view of how the bodies appear in the sky is displayed.  There are three options:" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""View Overhead"" is selected (the default), the view is from the inside of the celestial sphere, as it was on the 2102-A and 2102-B Star Finders.  The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "diagram is oriented as if it were being held overhead while looking at the sky:  if the ""N"" is to the north, east is to the right.  Azimuth increases " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "counterclockwise." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""View ""Star Finder"""" is selected, the view is from the outside of the celestial sphere, the way it is on the 2102-D and 2102-C Star Finders.  Azimuth " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "increases clockwise." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "In either of these cases, the center of the diagram represents the zenith, and the outer circle represents the horizon.  The default view has south at " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the bottom (view toward south), but it can be changed to view toward any of the cardinal compass points.  Circles of altitude at 15° increments are " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "shown:  the ones at the special JN altitudes of 15° and 75° are solid, while the rest are dotted.  Dotted azimuth lines at 15° increments are also shown." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""View Horizon"" is selected, the view is 180° of azimuth from the horizon up to 90° altitude.  The default view is centered on south (180°) azimuth, but " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "it can be centered on any of the cardinal compass points.  Lines of altitude at 15° increments are shown:  the ones at the special JN altitudes of 15° and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "75° are solid, while the rest are dotted.  Dotted azimuth lines at 15° increments are also shown." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The navigational bodies are represented by filled circles of three sizes:  the larger ones represent the first-magnitude stars and solar system bodies; " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the mid-sized ones represent the second-magnitude stars; and the smaller ones represent the third-magnitude stars.  There is the option of displaying " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "any combination of first magnitude stars and solar system objects; second magnitude stars; and third magnitude stars.  If the ""Show Names"" box is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "checked, the names of the bodies will appear to the right of their circles.  (The default is all bodies without names.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""Limit azimuth range"" is unchecked (the default), the entire available sky is shown (360º for the ""Overhead"" and ""Star Finder"" views, 180º for the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """Horizon"" view).  If ""Limit azimuth range"" is checked, the display is limited to the specified azimuth range." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""Show Helpers"" is checked, the positions of another 70 stars are analyzed and, if visible, the stars are displayed.  These stars are represented by " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "open circles to distinguish them from the 64 navigational bodies.  Their magnitudes are represented by the size of the circles, and use the same binning " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "as the navigational bodies, with an additional smaller circle representing fourth magnitude and dimmer stars.  These stars include those selected to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "complete the most recognizable asterisms (not constellations; e.g. the Big Dipper, not Ursa Major) that contain navigational stars, plus other ""pointer"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "stars, with the intent of making it easier to locate the body of interest.  Consistent with this purpose, when ""Show Helpers"" is checked, the check boxes " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "for the first, second, and third magnitude bodies become active but are disabled, forcing the display of all available bodies.  When ""Show Helpers"" is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "unchecked, the three magnitude check boxes return to their previous states.  The option to limit azimuth range is still available when ""Show Helpers"" is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "checked.  The names of the helpers are not shown even if the ""Show Names"" box is checked." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "As the mouse pointer crosses into the sky display, the pointer changes from an arrow to a cross, and the azimuth and altitude of its position is displayed " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "in the boxes to the right.  Regardless of whether or not ""Show Names"" is checked, when the pointer is over a body the name of the body will appear" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "in a box by the azimuth and altitude boxes.  (Note that if a smaller circle, representing a dimmer star is obscured by a larger circle, representing a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "brighter body, the name of the dimmer star might not appear.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Whenever ""View Visible Bodies"" is selected with ""View Overhead"" or ""View ""Star Finder"""", an additional function, ""Best Bodies Aid"", is available.  It is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "initially set to ""Off"", but if ""Two-body fix"", ""Three-body fix (boat)"", or ""Three-body fix (beach)""  is selected, red radial lines appear on the sky view, and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "two additional buttons, ""Rotate CW"" and ""Rotate CCW"" become enabled." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""Two-body fix"" is selected, three pairs of red azimuth lines appear.  The two solid red lines are separated by 90°, which results in the optimum cut " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(angle between LOPs) of 90° for a two-body fix.  A pair of dashed lines and a pair in a dash-dot pattern appear.  Each pair is 22.5° on either side of a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "solid red line.  If two bodies are selected, each within one of these matched pairs of broken lines, the cut will be within the allowable range of 45° to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "135°." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For a three-body fix, the optimum cut can be achieved with an azimuth spread between bodies of 120° or 60°, represented by the three solid red lines.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The 120° spread is recommended when at least 240° of horizon and clear sky is available, most likely on a boat.  When those conditions cannot be met, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "as when taking practice sights on a beach (unless a back sight might help), the 60° spread is recommended.  The ""Three-body fix (boat)"" and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """Three-body fix (beach)"" options represent the 120° and 60° choices, respectively.  The 120° spread is preferred, but circumstances might make the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "60° spread preferable even if the 120° spread is possible." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""Three-body fix (boat)"" is selected, three additional pairs of broken lines appear, one dashed, one in a dash-dot pattern, and one in a dash-dot-dot " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "pattern.   Each pair is 15° on either side of a solid red line.  If three bodies are chosen, each within one of these matched pairs of broken lines, the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "azimuth spread between bodies will be from 90° to 150°, meeting the requirement that the smaller angle between any two LOPs must be no less than " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "30°." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""Three-body fix (beach)"" is selected, to achieve the allowable range of cuts, the angle between the middle body and either outer body must be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "greater than or equal to 30° and less than or equal to 120°, and all three bodies must fall within a total angle of 150°.  This situation cannot be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "represented by pairs of dotted lines on either side of the solid lines.  Only two dotted lines, showing the extent of the 150° angle that all three bodies " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "must fall within, will appear.  It is left to the user to ensure that the other requirement is met." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "All of the sets of red lines can be rotated clockwise or counterclockwise in 1° steps, using the buttons (mouse only, no keyboard control), at a rate of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "about 10° per second.  This feature can be used in combination with any of the other features in order to select the best bodies for two- and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "three-body fixes based on cut, magnitude, altitude, etc.  If options are selected that do not use this feature (e.g. ""View Horizon""), the lines will " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "reappear in their last positions when an appropriate option is selected again or when switching between ""Two-body fix"" and either ""Three-body fix"".  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The lines can be removed by selecting ""Off"", but will return to their last positions if ""Two-body fix"", ""Three-body fix (boat)"", or ""Three-body fix (beach)"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "is selected again." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note that there is some distortion in these views compared to the actual sky, especially with the ""Horizon"" view, but the altitudes and azimuths " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "observed here should be comparable to those obtained with ""List Visible Bodies"".  In the ""Horizon"" view there is increased distortion at higher altitudes - " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the higher the altitude, the more the ""sky"" is stretched horizontally.  Also note that if the time of sunrise, sunset, moonrise, or moonset is used, the Sun " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "or Moon will not appear on the list or views, because, as explained earlier, the times are based on the Sun's or Moon's upper limb, but their visibility is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "based on their centers." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If ""Star Finder Data"" is selected, a table with data which a student would need to manually set a Star Finder is displayed.  This includes zone description; " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "GMT (UT); GHA of Aries; LHA of Aries; GHA, RA, and Dec of the Sun and Moon; and the SHA, RA, and Dec of the planets." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If latitude, longitude, or time zone is changed, activating ""List Visible Bodies"", ""View Visible Bodies"", or ""Star Finder Data"", or changing the state of any of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the view check boxes automatically updates twilight times, the visible bodies list, the visible bodies views, and the star finder data." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The entered DR latitude is used to compute the altitudes and azimuths of the visible bodies.  In order to more closely match what would be found with a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Rude Star Finder, the DR latitude can be changed to the latitude of the appropriate blue Star Finder template before continuing." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The program can also be used as a star (or planet) identifier by using one of the ""views"" with ""Show Names"" checked, or by matching the altitude and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "azimuth of the unknown body with one on one of the tables of visible objects, for that date, time, and location." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  See Help>General>""Almanac"" Accuracy." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Azimuths and altitudes of the visible bodies are calculated quite accurately (better than can be achieved with a Rude Star Finder), but are displayed to" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the nearest degree.  In practice, additional precision is unwarranted, as it is unlikely that the sights will be taken at precisely the time used in the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculation, and a typical sextant Galilean telescope has a 4° field of view (prismatic telescopes 7°).  However, in the upper part of the form, the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "azimuths of the Sun and Moon, when either the upper limb or the center of the body is selected, are shown to the nearest tenth of a degree.  (Prior to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "V5.1.5, the azimuths of only the upper limbs were shown, to whole degrees, when on the visible horizon.  This was changed so comparisons with the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "azimuth of the center could be made easily.)  Magnitudes of the planets are approximate and are rounded to tenths.  The magnitudes of Venus, Mars, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and Jupiter are expected to be within 0.2 of the values in the Nautical Almanac.  The magnitude of Saturn may differ by more because the angle of its " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rings is not considered in the calculation." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Times of Sun rising and setting phenomena are rounded to whole minutes and are generally accurate to within one minute, about the accuracy " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "achievable with the Nautical Almanac.   (The one minute difference can be due to an actual variance of less than one second and the subsequent " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rounding to whole minutes.)  The azimuths are rounded to whole degrees.  " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "With the ""Approximate Moon rise and set data"" box unchecked, the times of moonrise and moonset are rounded to whole minutes and are accurate to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "about one minute, except at high latitudes, where the uncertainty may reach several minutes.  For low to middle latitudes, manual calculations done " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "with the Nautical Almanac ""precise"" (Table I and Table II) method should agree fairly well, but those done with the ""approximate"" method (daily pages " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "only) can be off by almost an hour at high latitudes.  With the ""Approximate Moon rise and set data"" box checked, the times should agree with an " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """approximate"" method calculation within one minute; the azimuths will also be approximate, based on the approximate time calculated.  Azimuths are " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "rounded to whole degrees.   Percent illumination is rounded to whole percent." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Often the differences between the Sun rise and set times and the twilight times calculated by Celestial Tools and those of the tables on the daily pages " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of the Nautical Almanac are a result of the fact that the Nautical Almanac tables are calculated for the middle day of the three days shown on a page, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "but are applied to all three days." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "There is the potential for a one minute difference between times calculated using Auto ZD and those calculated using Manual ZD.  Each is an " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "independent calculation, and the difference can arise because of rounding." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "For ""List Visible Bodies"" and related functions, altitudes and azimuths are rounded to whole degrees.  (Note that a calculated azimuth of 359.5° or " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "greater is shown rounded to 360°, not 000°, so as to retain its proper position when visible bodies are listed in order of increasing azimuth.) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "In order to speed up the display of results on older, slower computers, the Sun-Moon calculation is done with five-minute resolution instead of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "one-minute resolution.  This could potentially result in a ""from"" time that is as much as four minutes late and a ""to"" time that is as much as four minutes " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "early.  For its intended purpose, this should be of no concern.  (Another slight error is due to the fact that the calculations are done with values of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "altitude and azimuth that have already been rounded to the nearest degree, but this is minor.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
