			"NOON SIGHT" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a. Purpose:  Calculate the zone time of Local Apparent Noon to the nearest second.  (This is done by the GHA method.)  Calculate latitude from a noon " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sight.  Calculate latitude and longitude from observed zone time of LAN." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "b. Operation:  Required inputs for zone time of LAN are date and DR longitude.   Zone description is automatically calculated based on longitude, but " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "any civil standard time zone can be entered manually to allow for time zones not based on longitude, or for Universal Time.  As a convenience feature, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the UT (GMT) option forces time outputs to be in Universal Time.  Check the ""DST"" box if the timepiece is set for Daylight Savings Time.  Any of the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "entered values can be changed at any time and the calculations redone.  Press the ""Get Zone Time of LAN"" button to complete the calculation." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "In order to calculate latitude from a noon sight or longitude from observed zone time of LAN, the Observed ZT of LAN must have a value.  It cannot be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "left blank. (The ""Noon Sight"" button will not appear until there is a value.)  In the case of a noon sight for a sight folder, the zone description will be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "correct, based on the entered longitude of the known position, and the ZT of LAN will be accurate.  If this is done, that value will be automatically " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "inserted into the ""Observed ZT of LAN"" box, but it can be changed to the actual observed time, within the range of 111328 to 124427 (121328 to " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "134427 if ""DST"" is checked) if Auto ZD is selected, the extreme values during the available years of the program at the far west and east ends of a time " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "zone.  (When Manual ZD or UT (GMT) is selected, the time can fall outside this range.)  At sea, where DR longitude is just an estimate, the calculated ZT " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "of LAN gives the navigator an idea of when to be on deck to start a series of sights to determine the maximum altitude of the sun (for latitude) and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "possibly the time of LAN (for longitude), a more difficult value to determine.  Watch time must be converted to zone time by applying watch error and " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "zone description.  If zone time then falls outside the specified range but can be corrected by adding or subtracting an integral number of hours " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "(probably just one hour, if the DR position is fairly accurate), then the zone description of the timepiece does not match the actual time zone.  Adjust " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the hours to make this correction, and adjust the zone description, using the Manual option, as required.  (If the timepiece is set for a non-whole-hour " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "civil zone description, not done at sea, the additional minutes must be taken into account.)" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Additional required inputs for calculating latitude from a noon sight are azimuth of the sun (north or south) or DR Latitude, sextant altitude, type of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "horizon (natural, artificial, or dip short), height of eye, index error, and temperature and pressure (defaults are standard values).  (When using " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "non-standard temperature or pressure, when the unit is changed the value is set to the standard value for the new unit.  If there is going to be a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "change in the units of temperature or pressure, it is recommended that the units be changed before a value is entered.)  All the options available in the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & """Sight Reduction and Fix"" tool are available here.  If the calculated ZT of LAN is used for the Observed ZT of LAN, as would be done when working from " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "a known position, the program uses this value and the declination of the sun at this time.  (It is unnecessary to enter the actual time of the sight since, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "even at the equinoxes, when the declination of the sun is changing the fastest, there is no significant change in the declination of the sun within 10 " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "seconds of LAN, the previous allowable limit for USPS Sight Folders, currently 30 seconds.)  Press the ""Noon Sight"" button to complete the calculation." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note for Artificial Horizons:  Although superimposing the Sun on itself is not recommended for artificial horizon sights, as of V5.0.0 Celestial Tools permits " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "this.  If Artificial Horizon are selected, an additional choice, Center, appears in the Sun Limb box.  If this is chosen, the center of the Sun is used in the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculation.  If Show Ho corrections as SR Form is selected, the altitude correction is done as it would be done using the Nautical Almanac:  the main " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "correction is obtained as if the body were a star or planet, i.e. semi-diameter and parallax are not included.  (Parallax is not zero but is considered small " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "enough to be ignored.)  If Show Ho corrections as Parameters is selected, parallax is included." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Note for Dip Short sights:   For a given height of eye there is a dip short distance beyond which only standard dip values (based only on height of eye) " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "are required.  If the dip short distance exceed the distance to the natural horizon for the entered height of eye, the program will automatically switch " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "the Horizon from Dip Short to Natural.   Note that entry of the numerical portion of Ds dist. is limited to five characters, including a decimal point, which " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "should cover all reasonable values." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Required inputs for calculating longitude from observed zone time of LAN are the date and zone description of the timepiece (from the ""Zone Time of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "LAN"" section) plus the Observed ZT of LAN, the time the sun reaches its highest point in the sky.  (Strictly speaking,  the maximum altitude does not " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "necessarily occur at meridian transit.  See the Accuracy/Resolution section below.)  This can best be obtained from the average time of equal-altitude " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "sights before and after LAN, or from a plot (or a curve-fitting program) of a series of sights starting before and ending after LAN.  Keep in mind that all " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "these methods require accurate sights, which are difficult to obtain, especially during the times of year when the altitude of the sun does not change " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "much around LAN. " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Press the ""Noon Sight"" button to complete the calculation." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Both latitude and longitude can be calculated from a noon sight without entering a DR latitude or DR longitude.  Required inputs are the date and zone " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "description of the timepiece (from the ""Zone Time of LAN"" section), the Observed ZT of LAN, plus the sight and sextant data.  Press the ""Noon Sight"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "button to complete the calculation." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If there is any vessel movement with a significant north-south component during the time of a meridian transit observation, the time at which maximum " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "altitude is observed will not be the exact time that the sun is directly on the vessel's meridian. This is because the rate of change of altitude due to the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "vessel's motion is greater than the rate of change in altitude that would be observed from a stationary position." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If you are only interested in longitude from observed zone time of LAN, it is not necessary to enter any altitude data, but any one of the ""At LAN"" " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "choices must be selected.  The resulting latitude calculation can be ignored." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "After activating the ""Noon Sight"" button, the program displays an ""Altitude"" box and a ""Declination"" box like those of ""Sight Reduction and Fix"", plus a " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "box showing the latitude computation.  If DR Latitude was selected rather than the azimuth of the sun, the difference between the DR Latitude and the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "calculated latitude is displayed.  It also displays a half meridian diagram illustrating the calculation.  On this diagram, ""O"" is the sun, ""Q"" is the equator, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and ""Pn"" or ""Ps"" is the elevated pole." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The longitude based on the observed zone time of LAN is also displayed at the bottom of the window.  If the ZD is correct, the longitude from the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "observed ZT of LAN should be close to the calculated ZT of LAN.  It should also be noted that because the calculated ZT of LAN is rounded to the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "nearest second, if that value is used to calculate longitude, the calculated longitude may disagree with the value of DR longitude used to calculate the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "ZT of LAN by 0.1'." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The ability to determine longitude from the time of LAN, in fact from the time of meridian transit of any of the 64 bodies included in the built-in almanac, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "has always been available in the Sight Reduction tool of Celestial Tools.  See the Sight Reduction and Fix Help for how this is done." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "If any of the data used to calculate the time of LAN is changed, all the calculated data disappears.  This is to prevent another calculation from being " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "done with an incorrect time." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "c. Accuracy/Resolution:  See Help>General>""Almanac"" Accuracy." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "The computed time of LAN should agree with a manual calculation within one second.  (If the value of the GHA Difference is exactly between two " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "tabulated values of GHA Increment, the minute/second value corresponding to the higher value is used.)  When Show Ho corrections as SR Form is " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "selected, the calculated latitude should be within 0.2' of the value obtained with a manual calculation using data from the Nautical Almanac.  The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "longitude from the observed zone time of LAN should be within 0.2' of the value obtained with a manual calculation using data from the Nautical " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Almanac." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "Because of the differences in the ways the tabular (SR Form) corrections and the parameters for the Sun are calculated, the results can be " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "slightly different for the SR Form and Parameters options.  This difference generally does not exceed 0.2'.  For the purposes of comparison to a manual " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "reduction, the SR Form option should be used.  Use the Parameters option only to see how the parameters change as the input values are changed." & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "" & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "It should be noted that for bodies with a changing declination, such as the Sun, culmination (maximum altitude) does not necessarily occur at meridian " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "transit.  The time between culmination and meridian transit is a function of latitude and time of year.  For the Sun, the time difference increases with " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "increasing latitude, and is greatest at the equinoxes, when the declination of the Sun is changing the fastest, and is zero at the solstices.  At the " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "equinoxes, the time difference is, in seconds, approximately 15.3 x tan Lat.  In fact, even at the equinoxes, the difference in the altitude of the Sun at " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "culmination and at meridian transit does not reach 0.1' until the latitude reaches about 88°, where the time difference is over seven minutes.  The " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "recommendation of starting to take sights 10 to 20 minutes before the calculated time of meridian transit guarantees that the peak altitude will be seen, " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "and an accurate latitude can be determined.  However, the time of culmination cannot be used to determine an accurate longitude.  The actual time of " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "meridian passage, which is difficult to determine, must be used.  But even at the equinoxes and 88º latitude, the time difference (7m18s), which " & Chr(13) & Chr(10) & "amounts to 1°49.5' of longitude, is only about 3.8 nautical miles." & Chr(13) & Chr(10)
